<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NBA's latest Proposal Has Several Significant Changes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 3 (Xinhua) -- The NBA's latest proposal to
its lockedout players would put greater restrictions on free
agency, impose an inflexible ceiling on team salaries and require
each player to undergo two random drug tests per year.
</P>
<P>
The 17-page document, dated September 24, was mailed to all
players and agents early this week. It contained no change in the
league's position on the core issue of the labor stalemate: the
league's insistence on imposing an inflexible ceiling on team
payrolls, or a hard salary cap.
</P>
<P>
The offer also, for the first time, gave details of the
financial terms for other parts of a new collective bargaining
agreement.
</P>
<P>
In this offer, the NBA proposed increasing minimum salaries
and guaranteeing the players' share will increase 50 million
dollars annually in the first four years of the agreement from
the one billion dollars they received in 1997-98.
</P>
<P>
But the NBA wants to reduce the portion of television revenue
that goes to players, eliminate the 25 million guaranteed
licensing payment to the union, limit performance bonuses to five
percent of salary and count all bonuses against the salary cap.
</P>
<P>
The increases in the salary cap based on guaranteed television
rights' fees would exceed 50 million per year.
</P>
<P>
NBA spokesman Chris Brienza said the league will not comment
on collective bargaining proposals.
</P>
<P>
"On the core issue of the bargaining, the NBA has not moved
one bit" National Basketball Players Association chief Billy
Hunter said through a spokesman last night.
</P>
<P>
"The owners still insist on a hard cap. To make matters worse,
they now have raised for the first time dozens of new issues,
many of which are extremely sensitive, and they are asking the
players to make concessions on each one.
</P>
<P>
Everything the players have gained through decades of
bargaining and arbitration, the owners want back with interest.
Clearly, the owners are not interested in bringing this
bargaining to a swift and fair conclusion.
</P>
<P>
The sides will resume bargaining on Thursday in New York, only
the second formal session since the lockout began on July 1 and
virtually all basketball-related activities ceased.
</P>
<P>
Training camps were supposed to open Monday, but they have
been postponed indefinitely and the first 24 preseason games
canceled.
</P>
<P>
Under the NBA's proposal, players would have to be in the
league for six seasons before they could be unrestricted free
agents. The rookie wage scale would be extended to five seasons,
but only the first three seasons would be guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
The players' team would have the option to renew the contract
for the fourth and fifth season.
</P>
<P>
As for the salary cap, the prior agreement allowed teams to
re-sign their own players for any amount, even if it exceeded the
cap. That caused some owners to view it as a soft salary cap. The
NBA proposed two formats in its latest offer.
</P>
<P>
In one format, the hard salary cap eventually would eliminate
exceptions. The change would be phased in over four years, with
teams allowed to be 20 percent over the cap for the 1998-99
season, dropping to 10 percent, Five percent and zero.
</P>
<P>
That 20 percent cushion is expected to translate to six
million dollars, which teams could use to re-sign their players
who have at least three years' experience. However, a team loses
that cushion if it signs another team's free agent.
</P>
<P>
In the other salary cap proposal, nearly all of the exceptions
would remain in effect, but if a team exceeded the cap, players
on that team could be forced to give up a portion of their
salaries.
</P>
<P>
The NBA proposed that the union could determine the formula
for deciding which players had money deducted from their
paychecks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
