<HEADLINE> U.S. Court Overturns Damages to Ticket Sellers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 3 (Xinhua) -- A federal appeals court in
San Francisco overturned 5.2 million U.S. dollars in damages to
six former SuperSonics ticket sellers who said they were fired
for complaining about the illegal cutoff of overtime.
</P>
<P>
If upheld, the ruling by the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
would permanently bar most of the damages on the grounds' that
the employees complained only to their supervisors and never
filed a formal overtime complaint with the government.
</P>
<P>
The court also said damages of 75,000 dollars per employee for
emotional distress were excessive, and told a federal judge to
reconsider a request by the team's management company to dismiss
the entire suit.
</P>
<P>
Spencer Hall, lawyer for the employees, said he probably would
appeal to the Supreme Court. He noted that the ruling conflicted
with the view of most other appeals courts that employees who are
victims of retaliation after complaining to supervisors can sue
under federal labor law. 
</P>
</TEXT>
