<HEADLINE> Roundup: Iranian-Afghan Tension Mounts Amid U.N. Peace Initiative </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 3 (Xinhua) -- As U.N. special envoy on
Afghanistan Lakhdar Brahimi resumed peace efforts in the region,
tension heightened between Iran and Afghanistan following the
alleged violation of Afghan airspace by Iranian jet fighters
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Afghan Taliban have accused Iran of violating Afghan
airspace and gave Iran a strong-worded warning not to repeat such
act.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban also appealed to the international community to
force Iran to refrain from provoking the Afghan nation.
</P>
<P>
Chief Taliban representative in Islamabad Saeed Ul Rehman
Haqqani said, "Iranian military aircraft and helicopters violated
Afghan territory when they flew over Herat, Farah and Nimruz
provinces bordering Iran."
</P>
<P>
However, a statement issued Saturday by the Iranian Embassy in
Islamabad categorically denied the report regarding the violation
of Afghan airspace. The embassy termed it as "the baseless claim."
</P>
<P>
There are also reports that the Iranian military aircraft which
flew over Afghan territory were on a reconnaissance mission aimed
at checking the position of Taliban chief commander Mullah Umar in
Kandahar, headquarters of the Taliban movement.
</P>
<P>
Tension mounted between Iran and Afghanistan when Iran charged
the Taliban with having killed its nine diplomats based in the
northern Afghan town of Mazar-i-Sharif when the Taliban captured
the town on August 8.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian authorities also announced that they would avenge
the assassination of its diplomats in Mazar-i-Sharif, the
stronghold of the anti-Taliban Northern Alliance led by deposed
Afghan President Burhanuddin Rabbani.
</P>
<P>
Iran amassed its troops last month along the Afghan borders
apparently for undertaking military exercises. The move offended
the Taliban who carried out an offensive against the central
Afghan province of Bamyan and captured it from the Shiite
Hezb-e-Wahdat forces allegedly supported by Iran.
</P>
<P>
Serious allegations were traded between the two countries and
Iran even accused Pakistan of supporting and equipping the
Taliban, a charge which has been repeatedly denied by Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
While the Taliban alleged that Iran, Russia and Tajikistan are
supporting and providing military assistance to their rivals,
leaders of the Northern Alliance, these countries have denied the
charge as well.
</P>
<P>
Brahimi has been given the task by U.N. Secretary General Kofi
Annan of helping ease the tension between the two Muslim countries
and prevail upon the warring Afghan factions to resume talks for
the establishment of a broad-based multi-ethnic government in the
war-torn country.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, there are reports that chief anti-Taliban commander
Ahmed Shah Masood is prepared to launch a large-scale offensive
against the capital of Kabul before the winter sets in and snow
falls.
</P>
<P>
Observers here believe that there is little chance that the
peace initiative by Brahimi will bear any fruit in view of the
tense situation between Iran and Afghanistan and among the warring
Afghan factions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
