<HEADLINE> Last Group of U.S. Embassy Staffers Leave Tajikistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 3 (Xinhua) -- The last group of U.S. diplomats
led by Charge d'Affaires Patricia Francis Calppeper left Dushanbe,
the Tajik capital, Saturday, the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. diplomats headed to an unspecified neighboring country
in the Commonwealth of Independent States.
</P>
<P>
On September 25, the U.S. State Department ordered the
suspension of U.S. embassy operations in Tajikistan.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman James Rubin cited the local political turmoil in
Tajikistan, the limited ability to ensure the safety of its
personnel and the general concern about threats to U.S. facilities
worldwide.
</P>
<P>
Tajikistan is adjacent to Afghanistan, which Washington has
accused of harboring Osama bin Ladin, the suspected mastermind in
the bombings of U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania August 7, in
which 259 people, including 12 Americans, died.
</P>
<P>
Washington told the Tajiks that the withdrawal of diplomats was
only a temporary measure, and it would not affect bilateral
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Dushanbe, however, expressed "deep regret" at the U.S.
decision, saying that "the government of the country has taken all
measures to ensure proper security of the embassy staff," Tass
reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
