<HEADLINE> 2 Palestinians Injured in Clashes in Hebron </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Two Palestinians were injured
in clashes with Israeli soldiers Saturday in the West Bank town
of Hebron as Israel briefly lifted a curfew imposed in the
Israel-controlled part of the town, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
In the clashes, Palestinians threw stones at the soldiers, who
fired rubber-coated bullets and tear gas in return, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
The curfew, imposed Wednesday after more than a dozen of
Israeli soldiers patrolling outside the Jewish settlement in the
city were injured by a grenade attack, was lifted for three hours
to allow Palestinian residents to buy food.
</P>
<P>
Hebron, home to about 450 Jewish settlers surrounded by more
than 130,000 Palestinian residents, has been one of the flash
points of conflicts after being divided into two parts
respectively controlled by the Palestinians and Israel under an
agreement signed early last year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, other areas in the West Bank and Gaza Strip are
still under full closure Saturday. The Israeli army sealed off the
areas Friday following security information that Hamas, the
Islamic Resistance Movement, was planning to carry out suicide
attacks in Israel.
</P>
<P>
Hamas has repeated the pledge to avenge the killing of two of
its military leaders since they were shot dead by Israeli soldiers
last month.
</P>
<P>
Also Saturday, Israel Radio quoted Palestinian police as
saying that they have foiled an attempt by Hamas last week to
commit suicide bombings in Israel.
</P>
<P>
Two Palestinians with about 60 kilograms of explosive were
arrested while trying to cross the border to the Israeli side from
Gaza, the police said.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian security has discovered a bomb factory with
hundreds of kilograms of explosive in Hebron earlier this
week. And Hamas said the cooperation between Palestinian and
Israeli security forces has made it more difficult for the
military organization to attack Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
