<DOCNO> XIE19981004.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: General Debate Mirrors Picture of Current World  (by Gu Zhenqiu) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, October 3 (Xinhua) -- The two-week general
debate of the 53rd General Assembly session, which concluded on
Friday, mirrored a general picture of the current world -- how 179
U.N. members and one observer interpret the opportunities and
challenges in the final years of the century from their own
perspectives.
</P>
<P>
At the general debate, which kicked off on September 21, 26
heads of state, 15 prime ministers and 105 foreign ministers,
together with other speakers, took the floor to air their views on
a wide range of matters of international concern.
</P>
<P>
Yasir Arafat, Palestinian leader, also delivered his speech at
the U.N. rostrum. It is the first time for a Palestinian
representative to address the general debate since the July
adoption of a Security Council resolution to upgrade the
Palestine's status at the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The general debate was held this year after nearly all corners
of the world at large have been affected by the spreading Asian
financial crisis, so that's why almost all statements have
expressed, explicitly or implicitly, the governmental concerns
over the pros and cons of globalization process.
</P>
<P>
Over the past two weeks, speakers, those from the developing
world in particular, have voiced their concerns over the profound
economic inequalities between the vast sectors of humanity
floundering in poverty or an inefficiency of resources, and the
minority living in prosperity and abundance.
</P>
<P>
Many of the statements have devoted to the anxieties prompted
by the rapid and inexorable process of globalization which is
reaching into all aspects of international relations.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, there is mounting interest in securing a deeper
understanding of the nature of the process in order that the
international community may prepare itself to manage the effects.
Many developing countries, such as Brazil, Ghana and Sri Lanka,
revealed a striking fact that the economic globalization not only
simply benefits a few, but also harms the weakest and the most
vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
In a bid to arrest the tendency of marginalizing the poorer
countries, various countries have cried out calls for a balanced
development in the world, and a fair South-North ties.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, the world also heard calls for a redefinition of
the rules to regulate current economic phenomena and to review or
readjust the existing multilateral financial structures, which,
dating back to the Bretton Woods agreements reached some five
decades ago, simply failed to meet the present needs.
</P>
<P>
It is the universal consensus, clearly and urgently reached
among U.N. member states, that since no country can stand alone
outside the whole world, "global problems calls for global
solution."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, speakers also touched upon the threats to the world
peace and security in such areas as Afghanistan, the Balkans and
the Great Lakes region. A number of statements constituted to a
feeling of frustration at the constraint which the 185-member
world body's lack of resources in taking necessary preventive
actions when the world is facing unfortunate deaths and
destruction.
</P>
<P>
What was most impressive was that most of the speakers have not
lost their confidence in the United Nations, calling upon the
organization to make headway in its reform drive and play a
central role in ending conflicts and creating opportunities for
development.
</P>
<P>
More effective efforts have been urged to better
conflict-preventive mechanism, which many developing members
believe will allow the United Nations to play its preventive role
more efficiently through its cooperation with regional groups,
such as the Organization of African Unity.
</P>
<P>
However, what was also impressive was that President Bill
Clinton of the United States, the leading economic power which can
not remain immune to the global financial crisis, devoted almost
his all statement to an anti-terrorism war, rather than discussing
how to solve the pressing financial problem in the world.
</P>
<P>
Of course, the problem of terrorism, seen as a global menace,
was one of the topics singled out with greatest frequency by the
speakers. But observers here said that terrorism is not the only
major challenge facing the world after the August 7 twin bombings
of U.S. embassies in East Africa.
</P>
<P>
On disarmament, numerous references were made to the May
nuclear tests conducted by India, which was followed by
neighboring Pakistan. New Delhi's outrageous move, which has led
to arms race in South Asia, prompted a large number of
representatives to be more peremptory in calling on countries
which have not yet done so to join non-proliferation regimes and
the Comprehensive Nuclear-Test-Ban Treaty.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. reform, including streamlining institutions, improving
efficiency and expanding the 15-member Security Council, has also
been a constant and recurring theme discussed throughout the
general debate. It is clearly and widely agreed that the United
Nations, considered the most appropriate but not the only tool for
grappling with all sorts of problems and challenges, must be
adapted to new times.
</P>
<P>
They all recognize that reform will be the outcome of a
undertaking that requires deep thought, careful analysis, a spirit
of cooperation and time.
</P>
<P>
The participants in the general debate have borne in mind that
this year marks the 50th anniversary of the adoption of the
Universal Declaration of Human Rights. South African President
Nelson Mandela said that the eradication of poverty and a balanced
development remain a top priority in safeguarding human rights.
Such a statement was echoed by representatives of the most
developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Didier Opertti, the newly-elected president of the 53rd General
Assembly session, delivered a speech at the closing meeting of the
general debate.
</P>
<P>
He said that "this debate has provided us with a unique and
invaluable opportunity to see how the Governments of Member States
view the world in these final years of the century, what problems
-- in the view of their leaders -- have an impact on the peace,
security and prosperity of nations and what direction the
international community should take in order to resolve these."
</P>
</TEXT>
