<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Officials Hike Salaries Amid Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 3 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert
Mugabe and top government officials have raised their salaries by
up to 20 percent despite a budget crisis afflicting the country,
a report reaching here said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe's state-owned newspaper The Herald Saturday quoted a
government gazette as saying that Mugabe's salary, last raised in
1996, would go up by 20 percent to 307,200 Zimbabwean Dollars
(about 9525.6 U.S. Dollars). Therefore, his total annual pay
and benefit package would climb to 507,000 Zim Dollars from
456,000 Zim Dollars.
</P>
<P>
Last month, Zimbabwean Finance Minister Herbert Murerwa said
that the government might miss its budget target to the end of
this year due to unexpected three billion Zim Dollars in
expenditures, said the paper.
</P>
<P>
The expenditures included Zimbabwe's military intervention in
the on-going conflict in the Democratic Republic of Congo and
civil service salary hikes, according to the paper.
</P>
<P>
In June, Mugabe, rocked by a series of protests over wages and
prices, awarded civil servants pay rises by up to 21 percent
although public service unions had demanded 30 percent wage
increment.
</P>
<P>
Over 18 years in power, Mugabe has repeated calls from local
industry and international donors to cut back his government,
which has 55 ministers, deputy ministers and provincial
governors.
</P>
<P>
Critics say that some ministries duplicate their functions and
could be merged to save costs.
</P>
<P>
Local economists in Zimbabwe also want Mugabe to trim by up to
15 percent the country's bloated civil service, currently
numbering over 180,000 and causing government overspending which
are largely responsible for high inflation rate now at 29.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
The Zimbabwean Dollar has depreciated by more than 40 percent
under import and speculative pressure since last January.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
