<HEADLINE> Ugandan VIPs Raise Women's Fund </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, October 3 (Xinhua) -- About 100 members of the
Ugandan paliament and other officials Saturday raised some 20
million Uganda Shillings (16,000 U.S. Dollars) for women in the
district of Masindi, 250 kms northwest of Kampala.
</P>
<P>
At the function organized by the Association of Women
Empowerment Through Community Action (AWETCA), James Wapakhabulo,
the national political commissar of the ruling National
Resistance Movement, praised the move and donated to AWETCA
first.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Internal Affairs, Tom Butime, and State Minister
of Defense, Steven Kivuma, are also among the VIPs who donated to
the program.
</P>
<P>
Chris Bakesiima, who used to work as a police commander in the
district and is now the police commander of the central region,
donated 150,000 shillings (120 Dollars). He expressed the hope
that the money raised can be used to empower women in the
district both economically and socially.
</P>
<P>
Many things are auctioned at the function which lasted more
than four hours. They include a bull, some goats, cocks and some
fruits.
</P>
<P>
The AWETCA was founded in 1996 by mainly women of Masindi
District. It is now a registed non-governmental, non-profit
making organization based in the district.
</P>
<P>
The bottle-necks to be tackled by AWETCA include low
productivity, rampant poverty, ill-health, illiteracy and lack of
modern production skills and knowledge among others.
</P>
<P>
Its key aims are to strengthen interaction and unity among
members for development, to provide opportunities for capacity
building and vocational training, and to improve the
socio-economic and political status of women. 
</P>
