<HEADLINE> Iran Seizes Over 1,400 Tonnes of Drugs in 19 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Deputy Interior Minister
Gholamhussein Bolandian stated here on Saturday that Iran seized
over 1,400 tonnes of various narcotics during the past 19 years.
</P>
<P>
Bolandian made the statement at a joint press conference with
head of the delegation of the U.N. Drug Control Program (UNDCP)
which arrived here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
He said that some 2,600 international drug trafficking bands
have been smashed by Iranian armed forces since the Islamic
Revolution in 1979 and during the past one year some 200 tonnes of
drugs were confiscated in Iran.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted that the seized drugs by Iran were only 10
percent of the amount produced in the region, mainly in
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
Bolandian said that Iran has strengthened its military buildup
along the eastern border with Afghanistan following the political
development in that country, particularly the control on the
country by the Islamic fundamentalist group Taliban.
</P>
<P>
Head of the UNDCP delegation and Vice Speaker of the European
Parliament Renzo Imbeni expressed satisfaction with Iran's
efforts to fight against drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
So far the international community has little knowledge about
Iran's campaign against drugs and the member states of the UNDCP
should have more knowledge about what Iran has done in this
connection, he said.
</P>
<P>
Imbeni voiced UNDCP's readiness to cooperate with Iran, saying
that the UNDCP will open its office in Tehran in the near future
to speed up its coordination with Iranian authorities.
</P>
<P>
He said that UNDCP will co-sponsor an international conference
on "Narcotics and Civilization" slated to be held in Tehran in
April, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Imbeni said that he held separate talks with Iranian
officials, including Interior Minister Abdolvahed Mousavi Lari, and
inspected Iran's eastern border. 
</P>
</TEXT>
