<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Initiative for Reviving Global Economy Endorsed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 3 (Xinhua) -- The initiative that the
United States put up on Friday to head off global recession got
endorsement from other major industrialized nations Saturday.
</P>
<P>
British Chancellor of the Exchequer Gordon Brown and Canadian
Finance Minister Paul Martin said they would use the Group of
Seven (G-7) meeting on Saturday to push various reform ideas.
</P>
<P>
Both Martin and Brown gave preliminary endorsements to the U.S.
idea to allow the International Monetary Fund to provide emergency
loans more quickly for countries embattled with financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
"As we meet here in Washington, we are conscious that more than
a quarter of the world is in recession, that the second largest
economy in the world, Japan, is in recession and that the social
casualties of the Asian crisis are rising in numbers," Brown told
reporters before the start of the Group of Seven meetings.
</P>
<P>
"There is a growing consensus on what needs to be done," Martin
said, calling the idea a "crisis prevention fund."
</P>
<P>
He said it had merit as did ideas being put forth by his
country, Britain and other nations to reform IMF operating
procedures and strengthen regulatory supervision.
</P>
<P>
The meeting by finance ministers from the United States, Japan,
Germany, Britain, France, Canada and Italy were setting the stage
for wider discussions at the annual meetings of the 182-nation IMF
and World Bank which get under way Sunday.
</P>
<P>
In advance of the G-7 discussions, U.S. Treasury Secretary
Robert Rubin met separately with Japanese Finance Minister Kiichi
Miyazawa. Rubin told reporters on Friday that the United States
still believed that aggressive actions on the part of Japanese
authorities to deal with weak banks and jump-start its economy
were key to resolving the crisis that began in Thailand 15 months
ago.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, U.S. President Bill Clinton suggested that the IMF
provide emergency loans more quickly to countries threatened by
the economic meltdowns that sent investors fleeing from three
Asian nations last year and from Russia this summer.
</P>
<P>
"This country has got to lead," Clinton said. "We've got to be
aggressive. We've got to stay on the balls of our feet."
</P>
<P>
Rubin told reporters that the United States would be pushing a
number of proposals to the finance ministers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
