<HEADLINE> Russia Hails Fishing Cooperation With Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 3 (Xinhua) -- The Russian Foreign Ministry said
Saturday that it hopes that the successful start of fishing
cooperation with Japan in the South Kuril area will help the two
countries find new forms of cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"The history of Russian-Japanese ties indicates that relations
in the field of fishing have traditionally served as an indicator
of trust between the two countries," the ministry said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
"This agreement is the result of new favorable tendencies aimed
at strengthening good neighborliness and partnership between
Russia and Japan," the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The accord was signed in Moscow on February 21, 1998, after
three years of hard negotiations, the Itar-Tass news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
It entered into force May 21, 1998.
</P>
<P>
For the first time in the 50-year history of territorial
disputes between Russia and Japan, the agreement has determined
the rules of fishing for Japan in the South Kuril area and the
procedure for exercising control by Russia, Tass said.
</P>
<P>
After the end of the Second World War, both the Soviet Union
and subsequently Russia had banned Japanese boats from fishing in
waters off the disputed Kuril islands.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Japanese fishers can catch up to 1,600
tons of catfish and 130 tons of squid this year.
</P>
<P>
"On the whole, as far as the Russian side knows, the immediate
participants in the implementation of the agreement on both sides
are satisfied with the organization and the results of fishing,"
the Foreign Ministry statement said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
