<DOCNO> XIE19981004.0020 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Better Fertilizers Supply Urged in Ethiopia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Action should be taken to
ensure timely and adequate supply of fertilizers to Ethiopian
farmers at affordable prices, the Ethiopian Vice-Minister of
Agriculture has said.
</P>
<P>
Vice-Minister of Agriculture Getachew Teklemedhin made the
call here Friday when he was closing the three-day third Annual
National Fertilizer meeting, reported the Ethiopian News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Getachew said that the importers should play important roles
in widening the fertilizers distribution network.
</P>
<P>
Offering credit to farmers for the purchase of fertilizers is
one of the most effective ways of increasing their use, he added.
</P>
<P>
The third Annual National Fertilizer Meeting forecast that
419,000 tons of fertilizers are needed for the coming 1999 farm
season.
</P>
<P>
According to the participants of the meeting, Afar,
Benshangul, Gambella, Somali, Harari and Dire dawa are the six
low fertilizer consuming regions in the country.
</P>
<P>
The average fertilizer consumption is only six kilograms per
hectare in these regions, they said.
</P>
<P>
Inadequate extension services, poor infrastructure and farming
systems, credit problems, lack of distribution network and weak
farmer organization are the main reasons for low fertilizer
consumption, they added.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia imported 470,000 tons of fertilizers in 1998 and
about 300,000 tons were used during the year, according to the
Ethiopian National Fertilizer Industry Agency.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
