<HEADLINE> Nigerian Head of State Seeks Support for Civil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Head of State General
Abdulsalam Abubakar Saturday met with former military leaders in
Abuja in a bid to secure their support for his ongoing transition
to civil rule program, a source in the capital said.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar's closed-door meeting with former leaders Yakubu
Gowon (ruling from 1966 to 1975) and Ibrahim Babangida (ruling
from 1985 to 1993) lasted about five hours, the source said.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after their meeting, Abubakar said that it was
convened to share ideas and views on the way forward, adding that
members of the armed forces and the police would be briefed of
the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Former head of state Gowon said that the meeting was held in
an excellent atmosphere and views were shared between the former
leaders and Abubakar.
</P>
<P>
Gowon said the former leaders has assured Abubakar that the
military will support him to hand over power to a civilian regime
next year.
</P>
<P>
He said that Abubakar's recent visits to the United
Kingdom, the United States, France and South Africa have done a
lot to give Nigeria a better image.
</P>
<P>
Former service chiefs and inspector-generals of police were
also at the meeting, the source said.
</P>
<P>
Two other former military leaders, General Olusegun Obasanjo
(ruling 1976 to 1979) and Major-General Mohammadu Buhari (ruling
from 1983 to 1985), however, did not attend the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Obasanjo, the only military leader who kept his promise to
hand over to a civilian government by giving up power to elected
president Alhaji Sheshu Shagari in 1979, is now under pressure to
contest for presidency under the current democratization program.
</P>
<P>
Abubakar, Nigeria's eighth military leader who took office in
June this year after the sudden death of late military leader
Sani Abacha, has promised to hand over power to an elected
civilian government on May 29, 1999.  
</P>
</TEXT>
