<HEADLINE> Jordan Urges Breakthrough in Israeli-Palestinian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Crown Prince Hassan,
the Regent urged a breakthrough for the Israeli-Palestinian peace
talks on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
He made the stance clear at a meeting here with Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat's deputy Mahmoud Abbas, also known as Abu
Mazen.
</P>
<P>
Progress was reported for the recent Washington meeting between
Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu on Israel's
second redeployment in the West Bank. A breakthrough is hoped for
later this month.
</P>
<P>
Hassan reaffirmed the kingdom's consistent and firm stand to
support the Palestinians in their efforts to establish their own
state with its capital in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Abbas briefed the regent on the outcome of the Arafat-Netanyahu
talks in Washington.
</P>
<P>
The Hassan-Abbas meeting focused on ways to transcend the
obstacles hindering the peace process which has been deadlocked
for 19 months, Jordan's official news agency, the Petra reported.
</P>
<P>
It was conducted in the framework of the continuous
consultation and coordination between Jordan and the Palestinian
National Authorities on the peace process, the news agency added.
</P>
<P>
Abbas arrived here earlier Saturday on a brief visit.
</P>
<P>
Jordan is one of the two Arab countries that signed peace
treaty with the Jewish state. The other is Egypt. 
