<HEADLINE> Egypt not to Accept Unbalanced Palestinian-Israeli </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa Saturday reasserted his country's position on any deal
between the Palestinians and Israel, saying that "no deal would be
acceptable unless it is fair and balanced."
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks during the Strategic Military Symposium
which is being held here to mark the 25th victory of the October
War in 1973 against Israel in the Sinai Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. initiative could bring about a progress but there are
some disputable details, he said.
</P>
<P>
The progress lies in the possibility of a general acceptance of
the 13 percent withdrawal of the Israeli troops from the West
Bank, he noted.
</P>
<P>
"All what we hope and work for is a fair and balanced agreement
that ensures equal commitments on both sides without pressures on
one side," the Egyptian minister added.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that dialog and talks are the best way of
dealing with problems between the Arabs and Israel under the
previous agreements and the land-for-peace principle.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright is expected to visit
the region later this month for further consultations with the
Palestinian and Israeli leaders following the Washington summit
recently among U.S. President Bill Clinton, Palestinian President
Yasser Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
"We are going to see how far the coming accord will be viable,
objective and balanced," Moussa said. "The extent of the proposed
deal being balanced will determine the reaction of the regional
public opinion," he added.
</P>
<P>
On the Turkish-Syrian stand-off, Moussa said if the situation
develops, it will be very dangerous, noting that there is a real
problem between the two neighbors but its solution must be brought
about through diplomatic and political means.
</P>
<P>
Turkey accused Syria of supporting the outlawed Kurdish
Workers' Party which has been fighting for autonomy in
southeastern Turkey since 1984.
</P>
<P>
"The Egyptian diplomacy will do its utmost to contain the
situation," he said. It is totally wrong to resort to force to
settle such disputes that could be solved, or at least pacified,
through other ways, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
