<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-03 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran's Non-oil Exports Down by 17 percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Iran's non-oil exports for the
first six months of the current Iranian year starting on March 21
fell by 17 percent from those of the same period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
The figure stood at 1.27 billion U.S. dollars, Head of the
Iranian Customs Mehdi Karbasian told the official news agency IRNA.
</P>
<P>
But the exports were up 40 percent in terms of weight, he
said, attributing the decline of the value to the drop in the
price of petrochemical products in the international markets.
</P>
<P>
Iran, a country that heavily relies on its oil industry and
tries hard to vary its income sources, fetched some 3 billion
dollars from non-oil exports during the past Iranian year though
the government had hoped to earn 5 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
However, the official said the export of non-oil products was
experiencing an upward trend in last Iranian month (August
23-September 22).
</P>
<P>
During the month, the non-oil exports registered a growth of 9
percent in terms of value and 117 percent in terms of weight
compared to the figures for the same period last year, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
