<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1500 GMT, October 4 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS -- Visiting Egyptian President Hossni Mubarak said
Sunday that Egypt favors diplomatic efforts in solving the
Syrian-Turkish dispute.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak voiced the stand in talks with Syria President Hafez
Assad right after he arrived here in the morning on a one-day
visit, according to the Syrian News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak said the disputes between Syria and Turkey should be
solved through diplomatic methods instead of force.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak will also travel on to Turkey Monday to try to head off
the potential military confrontation between the two countries.
(Syria-Egypt-Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - - - -
</P>
<P>
ISLAMABAD -- Afghanistan's Taliban said Sunday that they had
formally lodged a complaint with U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan
alleging a violation of Afghan airspace by Iranian jet fighters
and helicopters.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban militia said in a statement that they had sent a
letter to the U.N. chief, saying Iranian planes violated
Afghanistan's airspace three times during 24 hours on October 2 in
 the western provinces of Nimroz, Farah and Herat.
</P>
<P>
"If the Iranian armed forces continued such provocative
activities, the Afghan Islamic Emirate will not be responsible for
 the dire consequences of its provocative acts," Abdul Jalil, a
senior Taliban official responsible for foreign affairs, said in
the letter.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban claimed that 15 Iranian planes and 15 helicopters
intruded Afghanistan's western provinces of Nimroz and Herat, next
to which the Iranian forces were carrying out unprecedented
military maneuvers involving more than 200,000 troops.
(Taliban-UN-Protest-Iran)
</P>
<P>
- - - - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu declared
Sunday that Israel is not to be involved in the dispute between
Turkey and Syria, saying Israel will "take steps" to reassure
Damascus about it, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
He made the statement as tensions are mounting along the
Turkish-Syrian borders over Ankara's accusation that Damascus is
aiding Kurdish rebels in Turkey, an allegation which Syria denies.
</P>
<P>
The radio did not say what steps Netanyahu will take to
reassure that Israel will not be part of the dispute, but Israeli
Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai has ordered the Israeli army to
scale down its routine activities along the frontier with Syria to
signal Damascus of Israel's intention. (Israel-Turkey-Syria)
</P>
<P>
- - - - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu said
Sunday that there is a good chance for reaching an agreement with
the Palestinians and he is ready to pay the necessary political
price for it, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu's remarks came amid reports that Israel and the
Palestinians are expected to reach an agreement over the Israeli
withdrawal from the West Bank during a four-day Middle East
summit in Washington in mid-October.
</P>
<P>
Israeli and Palestinian negotiators resumed their open talks on
Sunday for the first time in more than one month.
</P>
<P>
Israeli cabinet secretary Danny Naveh met with senior
Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat in Jerusalem while the joint
committee resumed the talks on interim issues such as the
Palestinian airport in Gaza and the safe passage between Gaza and
the West Bank, Israel Radio reported.
(Israel-Netanyahu-Negotiations)
</P>
<P>
- - - - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russia on Sunday expressed "deep anxiety" over NATO's
plans to strike targets in Yugoslavia over the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the government said the use of force without
United Nations authorization would be "a crude violation of the
U.N. Charter, undermining the entire system of present day
international relations."
</P>
<P>
In Belgrade, Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov and Defense
Minister Igor Sergeyev met Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic
to discuss the growing threat of NATO force.
</P>
<P>
The Western alliance is gearing up for action in the Serbian
province of Kosovo although it acknowledges that the Yugoslav side
has moved towards compliance with U.N. demands on ending the
conflicts in Kosovo. (Russia-NATO-Kosovo) 
</P>
</TEXT>
