<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Farmers Renewing Government Land Contracts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Almost three-quarters of China's
nearly 900 million farmers have so far signed new contracts with
local governments to continue land use for 30 years.
</P>
<P>
China introduced a household contract responsibility system and
the land contract system in the late 1970s and early 1980s, with
most farmers signing 15-year contracts with local governments.
</P>
<P>
As these contracts began expiring, the central government
adopted a land contract policy to extend the contract for another
30 years and local governments have formed groups to help extend
the contracts and to help keep farmers happy, and more important,
enthusiastic.
</P>
<P>
One farmer in Henan Province, Chen Jinsheng, explains it
simply, "Land means life to farmers. I slept so well after signing
the new contract and I'll work harder on my land to get better
harvests."
</P>
<P>
In the city of Pingdingshan in Henan, where the extension of
land contracts is almost complete after two years' work,
agricultural output grew 17.3 percent in 1996, which is much
higher than the average annual growth of 5 percent before 1995.
</P>
<P>
In some economically well-developed areas, peasants are also
being encouraged to engage in large scale agricultural
production. So, as a certain number of peasants have moved to
industry and service trade in their localities, the land they used
to till need to be taken care of by other peasants on a voluntary
basis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
