<HEADLINE> Kuwait Urges Syria, Turkey for Self-restraint </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait Sunday urged
Syria and Turkey to exercise self-restraint and hold
negotiations in order to end their disputes, the Kuwait News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"Kuwait followed with grave concern the developments of the
recent escalation of tension between Syria and Turkey ... and
it urges both countries for self-restraint and seek to resolve
differences through dialogues," said a statement by the Kuwaiti
Cabinet issued after its weekly session.
</P>
<P>
Tension has drastically mounted between the two neighboring
countries after Ankara launched a rhetoric campaign against
Damascus recently and reportedly massed up troops along its
borders with Syria.
</P>
<P>
Syria and Turkey have been at loggerheads over issues of
separatist Kurds, water-sharing and the Turkish-Israeli
military cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has long accused Syria of backing the Turkish Kurdish
rebels, who have been fighting since 1984 for more autonomy of the
Kurds in southeastern Turkey and often launched across-border
attacks from their bases in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
And Syria has accused Turkey of forming military alliance with
Israel, saying that it threatens Arab security and undermines
Syria's bargaining position in peace talks with the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait called on Damascus and Ankara "to respond to efforts
aimed at defusing and containing the dispute and spare the
peoples of both countries as well as peoples in the region
more agony and instability."
</P>
<P>
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak flew in Syria earlier Sunday
for talks with his Syrian counterpart Hafez al-Assad on Syria's
dispute with Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak, who discussed Saturday the Turkish-Syrian tension with
Saudi King Fahd Ibn Abdul-Aziz during his surprise short visit to
Riyadh, will go to Ankara after his Syrian trip in a bit to ease
the tension. 
</P>
