<HEADLINE> China Looking For More Donations for Flood Victims (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 4 (Xinhua) -- China is trying to raise more
donations for the victims of its worst flooding in decades this
summer by staging another benefit performance at Beijing's Great
Hall of the People this evening.
</P>
<P>
The program, "Love the motherland and help build new homes", is
being hosted by the China Charity Federation (CCF) and a number of
groups, with backing by the Civil Affairs Ministry, which is
responsible for the country's disaster relief.
</P>
<P>
Over 1,200 singers and dancers from across the nation and a
dozen well-known pop singers and movie stars from Hong Kong and
Taiwan are taking part in the program.
</P>
<P>
The flooding in July and August on the Yangtze River and
Nenjiang and Songhua rivers in the Northeast killed 3,004 people,
affected more than 200 million people, and caused some 20.3
billion U.S. dollars worth of damage.
</P>
<P>
In late August, CCF, the Red Cross Society of China, and China
Central Television held a TV program that raised over 600 million
yuan (about 75 million U.S. dollars) in donations for flood
victims and another 2 billion yuan over the following weeks.
</P>
<P>
According to Deng Lei, a CCF official, the funds raised in the
past two months have mainly been used for emergency assistance and
basic needs of flood victims.
</P>
