<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Supplies of Consumer Market Up in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 4 (Xinhua) -- China's economic restructuring
has affected consumer goods supplies and sales, which amounted to
16.6 trillion yuan in the 1978-1997 period, or an average annual
growth of 9.6 percent when adjusted for inflation.
</P>
<P>
Sales in rural areas came to 1 trillion yuan last year, 13
times the 1978 figure, and in urban districts, 1.6 trillion yuan,
or 22 times the 1978 figure.
</P>
<P>
A buyers' market has been taking shape, replacing the decades
of shortages of a number of products. One recent study showed that
supplies of almost all major commodities meet market demand and
that some even exceed demand. The retail price index in 1997 was
0.8 percent higher than that of the previous year, and showed
negative growth this year.
</P>
<P>
Prices of many goods are now regulated by the market, except
for the fewer than 5 percent of goods that are still under
government control.
</P>
<P>
More than 90,000 new markets have sprung up along with new
forms of marketing like warehouse selling and chain stores. Urban
and rural sales combined were 1.7 trillion yuan last year.
</P>
<P>
A national survey showed an average annual disposable income of
5,160 yuan for each urban resident last year, 16 times the 1978
figure, while that of each rural resident was 2,090 yuan, or 15.6
times the 1978 figure.
</P>
<P>
There is a growing demand for newer, higher-quality name-brand
products, and exercise or body-building facilities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
