<HEADLINE> Russia Blasts NATO Plan to Use Force Against Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Russia on Sunday expressed "deep
anxiety" over NATO's plans to strike targets in Yugoslavia over
the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, the government said the use of force without
United Nations authorization would be "a crude violation of the
U.N. Charter, undermining the entire system of present day
international relations."
</P>
<P>
In Belgrade, Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov and Defense
Minister Igor Sergeyev met Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic
to discuss the growing threat of NATO force.
</P>
<P>
The Western alliance is gearing up for action in the Serbian
province of Kosovo although it acknowledges that the Yugoslav side
has moved towards compliance with U.N. demands on ending the
conflicts in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen said Friday that air
strikes against Yugoslavia could take place within two weeks if
Milosevic did not comply.
</P>
<P>
In the statement, Russia called on the Belgrade government to
comply with the agreements to end the crisis, which were struck
between Russian President Boris Yeltsin and Milosevic in June.
</P>
<P>
It said that both the Yugoslav government and the ethnic
Albanian separatists should comply with U.N. Security Council
Resolution 1199, passed on September 23, to stop hostile actions,
take urgent measures to prevent a humanitarian disaster and begin
talks on the political settlement of the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
"Military interference in the internal Yugoslav conflict would
not only fail to solve its reasons but on the contrary would only
deepen the confrontation and scuttle diplomatic efforts of the
world community to establish a Serbian-Albanian dialogue," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
Russia, a traditional ally of Serbia, has repeatedly noted that
it sees no solution to the Kosovo conflict through the use of
force.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper Dnevni Telegraph quoted sources close to the
talks as saying the Belgrade government was ready to offer
unspecified concessions to ward off the NATO threat. 
</P>
