<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scenic Lake in Sichuan Well-Protected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XICHANG, Oct. 4 (Xinhua) -- Duan Ruchang moved his restaurant
from the banks of Qionghai Lake to a spot 80 meters away to comply
with new regulations protecting the lake environment.
</P>
<P>
Because of comprehensive measures and support from people like
Duan, the once seriously polluted Qionghai Lake in Sichuan
Province, has become pure again.
</P>
<P>
"We live on the lake. Only when it has a good environment can
we have a booming business," said Duan, 53, whose restaurant stood
on the bank for seven years.
</P>
<P>
The second largest fresh water lake in Sichuan, Qionghai Lake
not only is a source of drinking water to two-thirds of the
population of Xichang where it is located, but also a major
tourist attraction in the province.
</P>
<P>
Fast development around the lake in recent years not only
brought unprecedented wealth to local residents but also gravely
polluted the lake environment.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, the city government decided to carry out systematic
measures to improve this environment. In May of that year, 24
gas-fueled pleasure boats were banned, and the following May, 628
fish raising net-boxes were removed.
</P>
<P>
In early 1997, "Regulations Governing the Protection of
Qionghai Lake" were promulgated, strictly prohibiting the
discharge of untreated waste water into the lake. As a result,
eight waste water treatment facilities are now in operation.
</P>
<P>
The regulations also prohibit the construction of temporary or
permanent buildings within 80 meters of the lake banks. Two
resorts have been built to absorb businesses moved away from the
bank.
</P>
<P>
The measures have paid off, as a recent survey shows that the
lake water has reached the directly drinkable standards set by the
State.
</P>
<P>
At present, wooden and electricity-powered boats can be seen
shuttling on the lake, while restaurants do a booming business in
the new resorts not far from the lake. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981004.0062 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Key Water-Control Project on China's Yellow River </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, October 4 (Xinhua) -- The Wanjiazhai Water-Control
Project on the Yellow River in China was completed on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The project was the third largest dam project in China after
the Three Gorges Dam on the Yangtze River and Xiaolangdi Project
on the Yellow River. Work on the 6-billion-yuan project began in
1993.
</P>
<P>
It is one of the eight power stations on the Yellow River and
is expected to provide 1.2 billion cu.m. of water for Shanxi
Province, 200 million cu.m. for Inner Mongolia, and 2.75 billion
kwh of electricity to north China, annually.
</P>
<P>
The dam is 982 meters above sea level and has a storage
capacity of 896 million cu.m. 
</P>
</TEXT>
