<HEADLINE> Layoffs in China's Locomotive Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, October 4 (Xinhua) -- China expects to reduce the
number of workers in its rolling stock plants by 50,000, or almost
a fifth of the workforce, over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
Wang Taiwen, general manger of the China Locomotive Rolling
Stock Corporation, says that the move is meant to make the
employment system more competitive by phasing out redundant
workers, increasing efficiency, and bringing the sector out of the
red.
</P>
<P>
China's locomotive industry has 34 rolling stock plants and
maintenance centers, with 230,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
To help laid-off workers find new jobs, the corporation plans
to set up re-employment centers, open training courses, and help
develop services and trades. 
</P>
