<HEADLINE> Taliban Lodge Protests Over Alleged Airspace Violation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Afghanistan's Taliban said
Sunday that they had formally lodged a complaint with U.N.
Secretary General Kofi Annan alleging a violation of Afghan
airspace by Iranian jet fighters and helicopters.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban militia said in a statement that they had sent a
letter to the U.N. chief, saying Iranian planes violated
Afghanistan's airspace three times during 24 hours on October 2 in
the western provinces of Nimroz, Farah and Herat.
</P>
<P>
"If the Iranian armed forces continued such provocative
activities, the Afghan Islamic Emirate will not be responsible for
the dire consequences of its provocative acts," Abdul Jalil, a
senior Taliban official responsible for foreign affairs, said in
the letter.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban claimed that 15 Iranian planes and 15 helicopters
intruded Afghanistan's western provinces of Nimroz and Herat, next
to which the Iranian forces were carrying out unprecedented
military maneuvers involving more than 200,000 troops.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian embassy in Islamabad, however, has rejected the
Taliban's allegations, saying it was an attempt to divert world
attention from "the student militia crimes" in the northern Afghan
town of Mazar-i-Sharif and the central province of Bamyan.
</P>
<P>
Jalil said the Taliban government is prepared to solve all
disputes with Iran through peaceful dialogue.
</P>
<P>
A recently held grand mood of Ulema (religious scholars) in
Kabul had decided not to initiate war with Iran but vowed to
respond if attacked by that country.
</P>
<P>
"We are showing restraint but will not remain the silent
spectator if war was imposed on Afghanistan," Chief Taliban
representative in Islamabad Saeedur Rehman has said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
