<HEADLINE> Fogarty Steals World Title After Corser Crashes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Britain's Carl Fogarty stole the
world superbike championship on Sunday after leader Troy Corser
crashed out of the races in Sugo, Japan.
</P>
<P>
Coming into the final event of the championship with six
points away from Corser, Ducati rider Fogarty won third place in
the first race and fourth in the second to take his third world
title by 4.5 points.
</P>
<P>
Corser crashed his Ducati during the warm-up and broke three
ribs to rule him out of the championship.
</P>
<P>
New Zealander Aaron Slight, who was just half a point from
Corser at second before Sunday's races, finished disappointing
seventh and sixth on his Honda.
</P>
<P>
Two Japanese riders clinched victories in Sunday's races with
Keiichi Kitigawa taking the opener and Noriyuki Haga second.
</P>
