<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Ready for Information Age </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Large-scale construction of a
national information infrastructure and the explosion of
Internet-using population in China have elevated the country's
accessibility to information, which, to a significant extend,
determines a nation's growth potential.
</P>
<P>
By introducing program-controlled switching systems and
fiber-optic technology, China has constructed the world's second
largest telephone network and third largest mobile-phone network.
</P>
<P>
China has earmarked 160 billion yuan (19.3 billion
U.S. dollars) for information infrastructure development in 1998,
of which 145 billion yuan is being invested to expand the
telecommunications industry.
</P>
<P>
The largest information network of China, China Public
Multimedia Information Network (CNINFO) is expected to become the
largest Intranet in the world. It was constructed in 1995, when it
was known as Chinanet, and was expanded in 1997.
</P>
<P>
It is currently serving 600,000 users. A recent net-promotion
in Beijing announced its ambitious goal of netting 10,000 users in
Beijing every week.
</P>
<P>
According to the Office of the information Leading Group under
the State Council, China's Internet population had reached 1.175
million by the end of June, double the number eight months before.
</P>
<P>
Observers say the affordability of personal computers is a
major reason why an increasing number of Chinese are entering the
digital world. Today, there are an estimated 15 million computers
in the country, most bought in the last two years.
</P>
<P>
Widespread computer education is another propellant. Most
middle schools and some primary schools in largest cities in China
now offer computer courses for their students.
</P>
<P>
However, an inadequacy of applications and Chinese language
information sources are the bottleneck to the information industry.
</P>
<P>
This has become one of the top priorities of the new Ministry
of Information Industry, the merged two former ministries -- posts
and telecommunications and electronics.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Ministry of Foreign Trade and Economic Relations
formally opened its official Website as a cyberport of foreign
trade. "It's an ideal tool for opening new markets and collecting
feedback to improve the competitiveness of local enterprises on
the international market," said Vice-Minister Liu Shan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
