<HEADLINE> Mubarak to Visit Syria, Turkey to Ease Tensions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
will begin a visit to Syria and Turkey Sunday to rein in tensions,
which have been on rise recently.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak phoned Syrian President Hafez al-Assad and sent a
message to Turkish President Suleyman Demirel Saturday about his
intentions.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak said his goals of the upcoming tour are to bring the
two estranged neighbors closer and spare the region fresh tensions.
</P>
<P>
The visit came amid escalating tensions between the two
neighbors in the past week.
</P>
<P>
Syria accused Turkey of massing military forces along its
border and Ankara's close military ties with Israel, while Turkey
lashed out at Syria for supporting Turkish Kurdish rebels, who
have been fighting since 1984 for an independent Kurdish state in
southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Turkish forces are preparing to carry out military exercises
along the Syrian border.
</P>
<P>
Turkish press said the exercises will go ahead or not depend on
whether Damascus continues its hostile attitude toward Turkey.
</P>
<P>
"The issue now is assuming crucial dimensions. There are
warnings hurled. This escalations must be contained," Mubarak told
reporters on his way to Saudi Arabia for a whirlwind visit
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The strained Syrian-Turkish ties is the focus of Mubarak's
talks with Saudi King Fahd.
</P>
<P>
"We have to curb and contain tension. Military threats must be
stopped. I am ready to do my best to this end in Damascus and
Ankara. Turkey is a sisterly country for all of us, and any
military action involving it and Syria is unacceptable," Mubarak
said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the Middle East as a whole can not afford further
tensions or a new war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
