<HEADLINE> EU Willing to Send Peace-keeping Mission to Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, October 4 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) has said
that a negotiated cease-fire is the only solution to the crisis in
the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) and expressed its
willingness to send a peace-keeping mission to the country.
</P>
<P>
Visiting EU special envoy for the Great Lakes region Aldo
Ajello said here Saturday that a military solution will not work
and EU is ready to consider the issue of assisting with a
peace-keeping mission if the matter is brought up through the
Organization of African Unity (OAU) and the United Nations,
according to Sunday Times newspaper.
</P>
<P>
"We are looking for an agreement on a cease-fire as soon as
possible because we don't believe the problem can be solved by
military means," the envoy said.
</P>
<P>
Although some of the countries involved in the conflict might
have legitimate security interests, it is necessary to protect
DRC territorial integrity, he added.
</P>
<P>
Ajello warned that the involvement of any more countries in
the conflict risks escalating to a level where it could spread
beyond the Great Lakes region.
</P>
<P>
The EU envoy held talks Saturday on the conflict in DRC with
Zambian President Frederick Chiluba, who was mandated by southern
African leaders44[jJ%Q"P~crisis.
</P>
<P>
Ajello, who has visited South Africa, Mozambique and Namibia,
will also go to Rwanda and Angola during his current African
trip. 
