<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "Mislabeled" Vaccines Samples Sent to Switzerland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Samples of the Hungarian-made
vaccines that caused side effects on hundreds of Jordanian
students have been sent to Switzerland for further laboratory
test, the semi-official Jordan Times reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The further test of the vaccines labeled by the manufacturer as
"D&AMP;T" (anti-diphtheria and -tetanus vaccines) will take some time
but reasons behind the incident will be given upon completion of
the test, President of the Jordan Medical Association Bassem
Dajani told the paper late Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Dajani did not elaborate on the name of the Swiss laboratory
and that of the Hungarian pharmaceutic manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
An immunization campaign started on September 16 in Jordan and
a total of 25,744 students were inoculated with the vaccines
across the country. But over 500 primary and high school students
hospitalized for suffering dizziness, nausea and headache after
the vaccination. Incidents began to surface on Thursday and most
of the students referred to hospitals have been discharged.
</P>
<P>
All the vaccines used on the students were manufactured in
Hungary and donated by the United Nations Children's Fund to the
Jordanian Ministry of Health and Health Care last year.
</P>
<P>
The United Nation International Children's Emergency Fund's
representative to Jordan Mislak Elias earlier this week said that
the vaccines met all the required international and national
standards at the time of their delivery to the Jordanian ministry.
</P>
<P>
However, local papers reported that a special Jordanian
investigation team, which was formed right after the incidents
earlier this week, thought that mislabeling of some vials
containing the vaccines might be a possible reason behind the
incidents.
</P>
<P>
It was very possible that the Hungarian manufacturers had
mislabeled some of these vaccines as "D&AMP;T" when they were actually
vaccines against diphtheria, tetanus as well as a third disease,
the investigators told local papers.
</P>
<P>
Vaccines against three diseases, instead of only against
diphtheria and tetanus, were too powerful for those at school ages
and side effects will follow, they added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
