<HEADLINE> Four Britons Kidnapped in Chechnya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Four British nationals were
kidnapped Saturday in Russia's breakaway republic of Chechnya, the
Interfax news agency reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Britons, identified as Shaw Stanley, Peter Kennedy, Dare
Hikey and Rudolph Pechi, were seized after 20 people wearing
camouflage uniforms stormed into a house where they lived.
</P>
<P>
They were in Chechnya to install a mobile telephone system,
said Shaid Bargishev, head of the Department for Combating
Kidnapping.
</P>
<P>
Chechnya, located in the northern Caucasus, has been plagued by
a spree of kidnappings, mostly for ransoms, in the past few years.
</P>
<P>
The body of Akmal Saidov, a deputy to the Russian government's
representative in Chechnya, was found Saturday, five days after
being kidnapped by a group of gunmen.
</P>
<P>
Valentin Vlasov, Russian President Boris Yeltsin's personal
special representative to Chechnya, remains in captivity, more
than five months after he was kidnapped by unidentified
assailants on May 1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
