<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-04 08:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan to Sell More Shares of National </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, October 4 (Xinhua) -- The Jordanian government has
revised its privatization plan of the Jordan Telecommunication
Corporation (JTC) to market another 9 percent of its shares.
</P>
<P>
This move will increase the total shares available for
non-governmental sector to 49 percent, the semi-official Jordan
Times reported on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
In the latest amendment to the privatization plan, the
government said that the 9 percent shares can be sold either
to the JTC's employees on preferential terms or to provident
funds of other state-owned enterprises, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The amendment did not give the reason for revising the
previous plan, which stipulates that 40 percent of the JTC's
shares will be sold to a foreign investor and the rest will be
kept in the hands of the government.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a local analyst, who asked not be named, told Xinhua
that the revision might be made in response to the JTC's new
Chairman of the Board of Directors Ali Shukri's demand that any
reform of the corporation should put the interests of the local
employees first.
</P>
<P>
When Shukri was appointed in July to head the JTC, he
immediately began to criticize the government's plan, saying that
if 40 percent of the shares will be sold, then priority should be
given to the Jordanians, especially the JTC's employees instead of
a foreign investor.
</P>
<P>
The employees at the JTC should get shares whose quantity
corresponds to their years of service at the corporation, he
added.
</P>
<P>
The privatization plan of the JTC was unveiled in 1997 in
order to draw private investment, update its technology, establish
incentive management mechanism and finally increase the company's
profits by a large margin.
</P>
<P>
The British Cable and Wireless Company and the United States
Southern Bell Company have made their offers to buy 40 percent of
the shares of the national telecommunication giant, whose total
assets stand at 1.2 billion U.S. dollars. The government has asked
the two companies to submit their final bids by mid-October.
</P>
<P>
The partial sale of the JTC shares will make Jordan the first
Arab country to allow private or foreign ownership of its
established telecommunication network.
</P>
<P>
The government is now facing opposition from the parliament
in pushing through the plan. The plan has not been legalized
yet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981004.0094 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-04 08:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Cautiously Stay Away From Turkey-Syria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 4 (Xinhua) -- As tensions are mounting
between Turkey and Syria, Israel has ordered its armed forces to
scale down their routine activities along its borders with Syria,
cautiously avoiding to be accused of involvement in the dispute.
</P>
<P>
Israeli newspapers reported Sunday that Defense Minister
Yitzhak Mordechai has issued a statement saying that Israel is
not interested in any conflict with Syria.
</P>
<P>
"In order to make it clear beyond a shadow of a doubt that
Israel is not a party in this matter, I have given instructions to
decrease some of the routine activities along the border between
Israel and Syria," said the statement, which was issue Saturday
night.
</P>
<P>
The statement came as the tensions between Turkey and Syria
were flaring up over Ankara's accusation that Damascus is aiding
Kurdish rebels in Turkey, an allegation which Syria denies.
</P>
<P>
Turkey is reportedly building up military forces along its
border with Syria. Turkish Prime Minister Mesut Yilmaz was
quoted as saying the army was planning an exercise along the
border.
</P>
<P>
In another dispute area, Syria is blaming Turkey for its
increasing military ties with Israel, but Turkey and Israel deny
that their military cooperation aims against any third country.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Syria also have disputes over water resources.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
