<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800, GMT October 4 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI -- U.S. President Bill Clinton has written a
"thoughtful and positive" letter to Indian Prime Minister Atal
Behari Vajpayee, according to the Indian Express daily here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
In the letter, Clinton explained the deferment of his trip to
India which had been planned for November this year and welcomed
the progress made in the Indo-U.S. talks following India's nuclear
tests in May. The communication would keep the two leaders in more
frequent contact directly in the weeks ahead as they work more
closely to bring the dialogue between the two countries to
fruition, said the newspaper. (India-US President-Vajpayee)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ROME -- Italian Communist Refoundation leader Fausto
Bertinotti, ignoring a last-ditch appeal from Premier Romano
Prodi, reiterated Saturday his opposition to the government's 1999
budget bill.
</P>
<P>
Opening a two-day meeting of his party's policy-making
committee, the secretary of the Refoundation proposed "giving the
parliamentary groups a mandate to vote against this budget and
withdraw confidence from the Prodi government." Prodi's
center-left coalition relies on the hard-left parties' 34 deputies
in the Lower House to pass legislations, including the budget
bill. (Italy-Budget-Opposition)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The top financial officials of the Group of Seven
(G7) industrialized countries said Saturday that they would make
joint efforts to end the world's financial crisis and avoid a
global recession.
</P>
<P>
In a day-long meeting in Washington, finance ministers and
central bank governors from the seven countries -- Canada,
Britain, France, Germany, Italy, Japan and the United States --
focused their discussions on the current economic crisis and
committed cooperative efforts in dealing with the problems. A
joint statement issued after the meeting said the ministers
reaffirmed the key importance of "each country in the global
economy doing its part to promote recovery and financial
stability." (US-G7-Meeting)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- The Yugoslav Foreign Ministry Saturday strongly
condemned the recent attacks on Yugoslav frontier troops by
terrorists who entered Yugoslavia from Albania.
</P>
<P>
In a protest note to the Albanian Embassy in Yugoslavia, the
foreign ministry said a group of terrorists assaulted Yugoslav
frontier guards with guns and antitank grenades last Wednesday,
killing five soldiers and injuring two. Noting that the invasions
had resulted from connivance of the Albanian authorities, the
ministry urged them to strictly carry out international duties and
take measures to stop invasions on Yugoslav territory.
(Yugoslavia-Protest Note) 
</P>
</TEXT>
