<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-04 08:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti Government Fails to Mend Fence With Labor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait's Ministry of Social
Affairs and Labor failed to mend its fence with Kuwait Labor Union
because the minister wanted to discuss their disputes with the
union's head instead of its executive council.
</P>
<P>
Head of the union Thabet Al-Haroun rejected Saturday the
request of Social Affairs and Labor Minister Jassem Al-Oun to
discuss the union's complaints submitted to the International
Labor Organization (ILO), Kuwaiti press reports said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Mohammad Al-Salman, the union's deputy chairman, said, "we went
to meet with minister Al-Oun in his office upon his request, but
we were surprised by the minister's request to meet alone with
chairman Al-Haroun."
</P>
<P>
Al-Haroun rejected the request and "it prompted us to leave
the minister's office because the union is represented by its
executive council, not by the chairman alone," Al-Salman said.
</P>
<P>
The union has complained to the ILO that Kuwaiti government
banned the establishment of unions in some sectors, privatized
factories and companies without consulting with the union and
refused to take into account the union's request to amend the
country's labor law, the reports said.
</P>
<P>
He said the government deliberately ignored the union's views,
which speaks on behalf of the Kuwaiti workers.
</P>
<P>
The union has urged the ILO to "intervene in the issue if the
government failed to find an amicable solution to the dispute,"
Al-Salman said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he stressed that the compliants do not harm the
interests of Kuwait and "we are always strong defendants against
anyone who attempts to harm Kuwait."
</P>
<P>
ILO Director Abu Baker Badawi has said that the ILO does not
aim to "penalize" the Kuwaiti government. But he underlined that
the organization may "resort to some pressure like publishing
reports and discussing the issue at the ILO annual conference."
</P>
<P>
Although some local observers expect an intensified rift
between the union and the government pending any agreement, few
believe such drastic decision as dissolving the labor union will
be taken by the government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
