<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Raise Funds for FESPIC Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's Public Welfare
Department will organize a Buddha amulet contest to raise funds
for athletes participating in the 7th Far East and South Pacific
Games for the Disabled (FESPIC) in January.
</P>
<P>
Phusak Thamongkol, the department spokesman, said his
department, as a fund-raising body for the welfare of disabled
athletes, was running well short of the required budget,
according to Sunday's Bangkok Post.
</P>
<P>
The FESPIC games, to be staged from January 10-16 next year, is
 expected to draw some 400 athletes from 42 countries and
regions. They will compete in 15 sporting events in Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
Phusak said government funds were insufficient to absorb the
costs of training, catering as well as rewarding the winning
athletes.
</P>
<P>
The department, therefore, decided to hold a Buddha amulet
contest on October 11 in the hope of generating at least one
million baht (25,600 U.S. dollars) to foot the bill, he said.
</P>
<P>
The bulk of the fund is expected to come from registration
fees and the sale of amulets.
</P>
<P>
But Phusak is not optimistic on the fund-raising target as he
sees the event generating no more than 200,000 baht (5,130
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The department is also seeking a 920,000-baht (23,600-dollar)
subsidy from the government Lottery Office. But so far, it has
not heard from the agency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
