<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, October 4 (Xinhua) -- The following are major
news items in leading Israeli newspapers Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- The Palestinian cabinet said on Friday that it would
call on its negotiators to work with all their ability to
reach an accord with Israel during the visit of U.S. Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright. And Palestinian negotiator Saeb
Erekat and Israeli cabinet secretary Danny Naveh are due to
meet on Sunday for discussions over the second redeployment of
Israeli troops in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Haaretz:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli National Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon, tipped
 as a possible foreign minister after an agreement is signed on
the second West Bank redeployment, has said that "under certain
conditions" he would be ready to accept the post. Sharon told
Haaretz that he could see himself as foreign minister if he is
allowed "to act to strengthen the country" and to contribute to
achieving peace "with a minimum of danger to Israel."
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- With tensions rising between Turkey and Syria, Israeli
Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai indicated on Saturday that
Israel was not a party to the tension and ordered Israeli troops
to step down some of their routine activities along the border
with Syria. "Israel is not interested in confrontation with
Syria, but rather in finding ways to renew talks," said Mordechai,
adding that the strategic relationship between Israel and Turkey
is not aimed at Syria. 
</P>
