<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak to Mediate between Turkey, Syria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
is to pay a surprise visit Monday to Turkey to mediate between the
strained neighboring Turkey and Syria, local Milliyet newspaper
reported here Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that Mubarak will first visit Syria on Sunday and
later fly to Turkey in a bid to find ways to ease the mounting
tensions between Turkey and Syria.
</P>
<P>
Turkish forces are preparing to carrying out a military
exercise along the Syrian border as tension is mounting between
Ankara and Damascus.
</P>
<P>
Local sources said that preparations had been completed for
such an extensive exercise but the date has not been fixed,
adding that whether the exercise would go ahead or not would
depend on whether the Syrian administration continued its hostile
attitude against Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Turkey accuses Syria of harboring militants of the outlawed
Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK), which has been waging a 14-year-old
armed fight on Turkish territory. But Syria denied the charge.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Defense Minister Ismet Sezgin said Saturday that "We
have warned Syria not to allow terrorism to become state
policy. It is unacceptable within the framework of friendly
relations and principles of democracy".
</P>
<P>
Milliyet reported Sunday that Turkish fighter planes from air
bases in southeastern provinces of Malatya and Diyarbakir were
carrying out low-altitude flights along the Syrian border.
</P>
<P>
A Turkish reliable source, who asked not to be named, confirmed
Saturday that Turkey has massed troops backed by tanks and heavy
artillery in the border areas with Syria.
</P>
<P>
Turkish President Suleymand Demirel said on Thursday that
despite Turkey's repeated warnings and peaceful initiatives, Syria
is trying to provoke the Arab world against Ankara by using
Turkey's close ties with Israel as a pretext.
</P>
<P>
"This is not a friendly attitude. I declare to the world
that our patience is running out and we retain the right to
retaliate against Syria", said Demirel.
</P>
<P>
Turkey enjoys close relations with Israel by carrying out a
number of agreements on military training and defense.
</P>
<P>
Syria said that the Turkish-Israeli alliance is targeted
against the Arab world, especially itself, accusing Turkey of
betraying the interests of the Muslims.
</P>
<P>
Syria has disputes with Israel over the future of the Golan
Heights captured by Israel in the 1967 Mideast War. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
