<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Private Airline Asks for Permission to Continue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Udom told reporters that he had met with Mahidol Chantarangkun,
permanent secretary of the Transport and Communications Ministry,
to discuss the request.
</P>
<P>
The ministry, Udom said, would meet Orient Thai Airline's
request because the government has a policy to promote the roles
of privately-owned airlines.
</P>
<P>
Orient Thai Airline received its five-year aviation license
from the ministry on May 1, 1995 after its overseas operation,
under the old name of Cambodian International Airline, was
terminated by the Cambodian government in late 1994.
</P>
<P>
The ministry issued the license on condition that Orient Thai
Airline would have to cease operation when Thailand's second
national flag carrier, Angel Airline, was formed and started
operation. The term was aimed at protecting the operation of Angel
Airline.
</P>
<P>
After Angel Airline started its flight service on September 20
this year, Orient Thai Airline asked the government to waive the
condition for it to cease operation and to let it continue service
until April 30, 2000, which is the normal expiry date of its
five-year aviation license.
</P>
<P>
In addition to Orient Thai Airline, Thailand currently has four
other privately-owned airlines -- Bangkok Airways, Thai Flying
Service, PB Air and Siam Land Flying. All these airlines are
expected to join forces in line with a government call to
streamline domestic flight service. 
</P>
</TEXT>
