<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reid Wins Hawaiian Triathlon Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Canada's Peter Reid clocked
eight hours, 24 minutes and 20 seconds to win the Hawaiian
Ironman Triathlon on Saturday in Kailua-Kona, Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
Reid, 29, who placed fourth in the past two years in the
annual event, took the lead from Germany's Jurgen Zack about two
miles into the marathon run, the last of the three sections of
the competition.
</P>
<P>
Belgium's Luc Van Lierde, who set the course record of 8:04.08
in 1996, wound up second in 8:31.57 ahead of another German Lot
har Leder, in 8:32.57.
</P>
<P>
Reid placed 54th in the 2.4-mile swim in the ocean, but jumped
to the third after the 112-mile cycling race.
</P>
<P>
During the marathon, Reid, the winner of the Australian
Ironman last April, moved past Zack and defending champion Thomas
Hellriegel of Germany. He beat his closest chaser by eight
minutes after 18 miles.
</P>
<P>
"The last mile was really tough," said Reid, who withdrew from
the race in his first two attmepts. "But then I thought I can do
it. I think I can do it. I did it."
</P>
<P>
Hellriegel, who finished second in the bike race, and was
running in third place in the marathon, began to walk after 11
miles and fell back several places. Zack also faltered
considerably in the waning miles.
</P>
<P>
Natascha Badmann of Switzerland won the women's title.
Defending champion Heather Fuhr of Canada was out of the top five.
</P>
<P>
A record field of 1,486 professional and age-group amateurs,
seven more than the previous mark set last year, began the
140.6-mile event under clear skies and with strong swim
currents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
