<HEADLINE> Tyson Psychiatric Reports Postponed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Nevada Athletic Commission
will have to wait for a couple of days to see Tyson's psychiatric
reports from doctors.
</P>
<P>
Reports from a five-day evaluation of the former heavyweight
champion closed on Friday, four days after they were due, but
now, the Nevada boxing authorities still hadn't seen them.
</P>
<P>
Tyson attorney Jim Jimmerson said he expected to have the
documents sent to the commission by Monday at the latest. Under a
judge's ruling, they will also be made public at that time.
</P>
<P>
"There's going to be some embarrassing things in the report,
I'm sure," Jimmerson said.
</P>
<P>
Jimmerson said he expected the report to be some 30 to 50
pages and summarize a battery of tests and interviews that Tyson
submitted to last week at Massachusetts General Hospital.
</P>
<P>
Boxing commissioners hoped to see the reports last week and
had set a hearing for Saturday to decide whether to license
Tyson. Now the hearing is expected to be held on October 19.
</P>
<P>
"I can't schedule a hearing until we have a documents," said
Marc Ratner, executive director of the commission.
</P>
<P>
Jimmerson went to court Thursday to try and stop the documents
from becoming public information. But a judge said he could find
no state statute that would prevent their release as public
records.
</P>
<P>
Tyson's attorneys have been negotiating with attorneys for the
two men beaten by Tyson in an August 31 traffic accident in hopes
of reaching a settlement before the commission hearing, Tyson is
still scheduled to stand trial on October 19 for the incident.
</P>
<P>
No negotiations are underway to drop the second-degree assault
charges, and prosecutors say they plan to go ahead with the case.
</P>
</TEXT>
