<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi PM on Providing Home for the Homeless </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi Prime Minister Sheikh
Hasina has directed the concerned authorities to provide shelters
to those who were rendered homeless in the devastating floods, an
English newspaper reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"We shall provide shelters in phases to all who became homeless
in the floods, river erosion or other calamities and by
deprivation through various projects," the prime minister said at
two separate public rallies held in southeast district during her
visit Saturday, The Independent newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
She assured the flood-affected people that her government had
taken all-out measures for post-flood rehabilitation and
reconstruction to recoup the massive loss caused by the
catastrophic floods.
</P>
<P>
She also asked concerned members of parliament and districts to
take necessary measures for providing shelters to the homeless
people.
</P>
<P>
"Our government is totally committed to managing two square
meals, two pieces of coarse clothes and shelter for the
downtrodden," she said.
</P>
<P>
While outlining the various measures of the government to cope
with the post-flood situation, she told the rallies that all
flood-affected people would be provided with necessary succor and
medicare facilities so that none was deprived of getting necessary
facilities from the government.
</P>
<P>
The government would provide food until the next harvest by
issuing four million vulnerable group feeding (VGF) cards among
the people who were most seriously hit by the floods.
</P>
<P>
Apart from giving VGF cards, the government would start
large-scale food-for-work, test relief and vulnerable group
development works so that the food victims could get job
opportunities for their survival, she disclosed.
</P>
<P>
With the disbursement of a 32.7 billion taka (695.6 million
U.S. dollars) agri-loan, the implementation of the 21.6 billion
taka (459.6 million dollars) agri-rehabilitation program and
post-flood reconstruction program, the government would enable the
nation to recover the losses (preliminarily estimated at 3.4
billion dollars) caused by the floods, the prime minister stated.
</P>
</TEXT>
