<HEADLINE> 2,500 Baby Sea Turtles Released into the Pacific in Mexico </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ACAPULCO, MEXICO, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Mexico's Guerrero State
Autonomous University (UAG) said Saturday that 2,500 baby sea
turtles were released to the Pacific Ocean on Friday after being
hatched in a turtle nursery in the port city of Acapulco.
</P>
<P>
UAG's Marine Ecology School Director Juan Vivantes Gonzalez
said so far this year a total of 22,115 turtle eggs have been
processed in the protection camp.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, they have released altogether 4,647 baby sea turtles
to the Pacific Ocean, Gonzalez said.
</P>
<P>
The director expected that after a few years the baby turtles
would return to the point where they were released to lay eggs.
</P>
<P>
As every year many turtles come to this Pacific resort,
biologists have proposed that the Barra Vieja area in Acapulco be
decreed a zone of protection. 
</P>
