<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Encourages Foreign Direct Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, October 4 (Xinhua) -- A Bangladeshi minister said that
his government has been encouraging foreign direct investment
(FDI) into the country since it came to power in June 1996, The
Bangladesh Observer daily reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina had also been extending all-out
cooperation to foreign investors, Commerce and Industries Minister
Tofael Ahmed said while addressing the launching ceremony of a
90-million-U.S.-dollar joint venture project for the production of
Scancem brand of cement here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The minister called upon foreign investors to come to the
country in a bigger way to avail the opportunities created
following the government's announcement of investment-friendly
packages of incentives.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the government was also encouraging the local private
sector entrepreneurs to boost the economy, he said, adding that
the government was extending all sorts of cooperation to the
private sector.
</P>
<P>
He said that there was now no ethnic problem in Bangladesh,
referring to the prevailing conducive environment for foreign
investment in the country.
</P>
<P>
The minister reiterated his government's all-out cooperation to
 foreign investors, saying that the government would try its best
to help in case of any problem.
</P>
<P>
The government gives a series of incentives and facilities to
foreign investors, including tax holiday from 5-10 years, 15
years' tax holiday for private power generation companies,
exemption of tax on interest on foreign loans, avoidance of double
taxation, six months' multiple entry visa for the investors,
facilities for repatriation of invested capital, profit and
dividend, and working capital loans and term loans from local
commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
By April 15, 1998, Bangladesh had absorbed 73.1 billion taka
(1.56 billion U.S. dollars) in local and foreign investment in
various sectors, according to the latest figures issued by the
Board of Investment. 
