<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> G7 Ministers Vow Joint Efforts to Halt Global Recession </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 3 (Xinhua) -- The top financial officials
of the Group of Seven (G7) industrialized countries said Saturday
that they would make joint efforts to end the world's financial
crisis and avoid a global recession.
</P>
<P>
In a day-long meeting in Washington, finance ministers and
central bank governors from the seven countries -- Canada,
Britain, France, Germany, Italy, Japan and the United States --
focused their discussions on the current economic crisis and
committed cooperative efforts in dealing with the problems.
</P>
<P>
"There clearly was a very intense focus on the issue with
respect to the current crisis, and a deep sense of commitment to
do everything sensible to deal with it," U.S. Treasury Secretary
Robert Rubin told reporters after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
A joint statement issued after the meeting said the ministers
reaffirmed the key importance of "each country in the global
economy doing its part to promote recovery and financial
stability."
</P>
<P>
The G-7 officials focused their discussions on Japan's economic
situation and Russia's financial problems as well as the group's
internal development.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that Japan's economic challenges have
intensified significantly in recent months and urged Japan to
quickly put in place programs to jump-start an economy that is
mired in its worst recession in 50 years.
</P>
<P>
"Strong sustainable recovery in the economy is of critical
importance to Japan, the Asia region and the rest of the world,"
the statement noted.
</P>
<P>
The group also warned of the serious dangers of inflation in
Russia if the country follows its announced plan of printing more
rubles.
</P>
<P>
They called for monetary restraint and fiscal adjustment in the
nation to avoid serious risk of inflation and further exchange
rate weakening, and urged Russia to take comprehensive financial
sector restructuring.
</P>
<P>
The ministers and governors welcomed the "impressive efforts by
a number of emerging market economies to strengthen their domestic
policies in light of the financial market pressures" that have
spread over the past year.
</P>
<P>
They also committed themselves to creating and sustaining
conditions for strong domestic demand-led growth and financial
stability.
</P>
<P>
The meeting stressed the role the International Monetary Fund
(IMF) has been playing in leading global financial stability. The
officials said that it was important to adapt the IMF to ongoing
changes in the world economy and called for increased
transparency, program reform and effective use of IMF resources.
</P>
<P>
But no action was taken on a set of proposals put forward by
U.S. President Bill Clinton on Friday or on ideas for overhauling
the global financial architecture advanced by other countries.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Saturday, Clinton made phone calls to British Prime
Minister Tony Blair and French President Jacques Chirac for
support to his proposals and received positive responses from the
two leaders.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. plan is centered on a proposal to allow the
International Monetary Fund to provide more, faster money to
countries threatened with a flight of panicked investors.
</P>
<P>
After the G7 discussions ended Saturday night, Rubin told
reporters that decisions on specific proposals were left until
later.
</P>
<P>
The group's communique said that Hans Tietmeyer, head of the
German central bank, had been made to head a working level group
and would report back expeditiously on any ideas where consensus
is reached. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
