<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Economic Growth Sustained Amid Asian Financial Crisis(2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Considering its enormous size, China is not entirely dependent
on exports for economic growth, according to Li Shantong of the
Development Research Center under the State Council.
</P>
<P>
In Li's opinion, China, with its 1.2-billion population, is
itself a huge market. "It is clear that China can achieve
sustained economic growth by stimulating domestic demand," she
said.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has been quick to react to the Asian
financial crisis to ensure 8 percent economic growth for this
year. Spending has increased dramatically on infrastructure
projects, such as railways, highways, power plants and
agricultural facilities.
</P>
<P>
The latest measure to stimulate consumer demand has been taken
by the People's Bank of China, the central bank, which announced a
cut in interest rates for bank deposits and loans recently. It was
the fourth such cut in the past year.
</P>
<P>
According to Liu Guoguang, vice-president of the Chinese
Academy of Social Sciences, measures designed to stimulate the
economy are beginning to play their roles in the second half of
the year.
</P>
<P>
The Asian financial crisis has elevated the status and role of
China, said an annual outlook report by the Singapore-based
Pacific Economic Cooperation Council. If China should devalue its
currency, it would likely start another round of competitive
depreciations in the Asian region, the report said.
</P>
<P>
A senior official of China's central bank also noted that
devaluing the yuan would not only be disastrous for Asia, but
would hinder the development of China's own economy in the long
run.
</P>
<P>
"China is a responsible country. It will keep its currency
stable for the sake of China's own benefits, the Asian economies
and the world economy as a whole," said Li Shantong of the
Development Research Center. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981004.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Economic Growth Sustained Amid Asian Financial Crisis(1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Amid the financial turmoil in
Asia, China seems to be the last bulwark against a further
collapse of economies. The Chinese government has vowed time and
again that it will not devalue the Chinese yuan and that the
country has the capability to achieve an econmic growth rate of
eight percent for 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Asian financial crisis, according to Chinese economists, is
not having much of a direct impact on the Chinese economy. One
reason is that the Chinese yuan at present is convertible only
under the current account but not the capital account, and the
country has enjoyed a favorable foreign exchange balance with an
adequate foreign exchange reserves.
</P>
<P>
However, the indirect effects of the Asian financial crisis on
China's economy should not be overlooked, according to Chinese
economists.
</P>
<P>
The crisis has forced some Asian countries to devalue their
currencies, making their export goods cheaper and thus affected
Chinese exports negatively. Chinese exports to Southeast
Asian countries so far this year have decreased in volume by
varying degrees owing to currency devaluation in these countries.
</P>
<P>
In spite of this, China is capable of tackling the tough
situation by adopting various measures, said liu Xiangdong,
vice-minister of foreign trade and economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Chinese exports to Europe and the United States have
picked up. In the first five months of 1998, Chinese exports to
the United States reached US$ 13.34 billion, up 18.1 percent over
the same period last year, and its exports to the European Union
were worth US$ 10.68 billion, up 25.5 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
