<HEADLINE> Eating Berries Can Help Lower LDL Cholesterol </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Fresh berries can
significantly reduce the building of low-density lipoprotein (LDL)
cholesterol, a culprit contributing to heart disease, stroke and
atherosclerosis, according to a research report.
</P>
<P>
The report, published in Saturday's Journal of Agricultural and
Food Chemistry, was written by a team of scientists from the
University of California at Davis, the University of Helsinki of
Finland and the Technical University of Denmark.
</P>
<P>
They wrote that blackberries have the highest LDL inhibitory
effect, followed by red raspberries, sweet cherries, blueberries
and strawberries.
</P>
<P>
During their vitro studies, they found that naturally occurring
phenolic compounds in fresh berries exhibited antioxidant
activities, comparable to those previously found in fresh grapes
and wines.
</P>
<P>
They said they need further study to determine the amount of
berries a person would need to consume in order to reap the
antioxidant benefits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
