<HEADLINE> Italian FM on Possible NATO Intervention in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, October 3 (Xinhua) -- NATO's preparation for a possible
military intervention in Kosovo is meant to persuade warring
factions there to opt for a cease-fire and open peace talks,
Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"There are still signs the conflict may be resolved, but it is
too early to say," Dini told reporters on the sidelines of a
conference on the euro which was held in Lodi, a town to the
southeast of Milan.
</P>
<P>
He added that so far "almost all diplomatic attempts have not
brought results and now we are at the ultimatum phase."
</P>
<P>
The possibility of a NATO military intervention in the troubled
Serbian province has been growing considerably in the past weeks,
especially in the wake of last Saturday's massacre of 16 ethnic
Albanian civilians, mostly women and children, by Serbian security
forces there.
</P>
<P>
At the beginning of next week United Nations Secretary General
Kofi Annan is due to report on whether Serbia has sufficiently
complied with the September 23 U.N. resolution demanding an
immediate cease-fire in Kosovo and the opening of peace
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
If it is found that this is not the case, Dini said, "foreign
intervention and even military action is inevitable."
</P>
<P>
Emphasizing that a U.N. mandate is required for that military
intervention, Dini recalled Russia's opposition to military
intervention in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Russia is a permanent member of the U.N. Security Council with
a power to veto any council's mandate for military intervention.
</P>
<P>
Kosovo, where ethnic Albanians make up 90 percent of the two
million population, plunged into chaos since February this year as
ethnic Albanian separatists intensified their campaign for
independence of the province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
