<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Albanian New Cabinet Formed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Albania's new cabinet, led by
Prime Minister Pandeli Majko, was sworn in Friday by President
Rexhep Mejdani.
</P>
<P>
The 19-member new cabinet was formed after former Prime
Minister Fatos Nano was forced to resign Monday after failing to
win approval for cabinet changes following riots triggered by the
assassination of a popular opposition leader two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the lineup, Majko had two days' intensive discussions
with the ruling five-party coalition and two non-party
representatives on the cabinet team.
</P>
<P>
The Social Democratic Party reportedly drove a hard bargain
over some ministers' nomination, which nearly spoiled the cabinet
formation. However, consensus was reached eventually.
</P>
<P>
A notable feature of the new cabinet is that the ministers are
comparatively young. Majko, 30, is Europe's youngest head of
government. Several other ministers are also in their thirties.
</P>
<P>
Political analysts say young ministers taking office marks a
beginning of a political juveniling of Albania, and the young
ministers-dominated government is likely to be bold and decisive
in adopting its own lines.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the members of the new government are believed to
have no connection with corruption and smuggling, which will make
them much less vulnerable to attacks from opposition parties,
analysts say.
</P>
<P>
"The main priorities of the new government will be a return to
stability, drafting a new constitution and the Kosovo problem,"
Majko told reporters shortly after the lineup of the government.
</P>
<P>
Those priorities will be the core of Majko's administrative
program to be presented to the parliament for approval on
October 5.
</P>
<P>
One day after being named prime minister, Majko inspected the
police department and said that it is time not only to attack
crimes but also to eliminate them, which shows restoring social
order will be one of the new government's overriding tasks.
</P>
<P>
Majko stressed the importance of cooperation between the new
government and international community, especially in economy,
saying it is necessary to enable the country to a normal life.
</P>
<P>
He said the government will support the financial policies made
in line with the International Monetary Fund's suggestions.
</P>
<P>
Dismissing reports that the new government is only an interim
one, Majko said some long-term goals in his administrative program
will be workable till the year 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
