<HEADLINE> G-24 Nations Urge G-7 Powers to Ease Monetary Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 3 (Xinhua) -- The G-24 developing countries
Saturday urged the seven industrialized countries to ease monetary
policy to restore tranquillity to the world financial markets.
</P>
<P>
In a communique issued in the wake of their 60th ministerial
meeting, the Intergovernmental Group of 24 On International
Monetary Affairs, which represents 128 developing nations, showed
their grave concern for the worsening global financial and
economic situation.
</P>
<P>
The group proposed to set up regional stabilization funds that
would intervene rapidly to head off financial crises such as those
which occurred in Southeast Asia and Russia.
</P>
<P>
They proposed the creation of a task force to review the
ability of international institutions to deal with the world's
financial chaos and find solutions.
</P>
<P>
They also called for faster actions on debt relief for heavily
indebted poor countries.
</P>
<P>
The International Monetary Fund-led workouts for heavily
indebted countries are slow and inadequate, the communique noted.
</P>
<P>
The G-24 meeting is part of the on-going IMF-World Bank joint
annual meeting. China is not a member of the G-24, but attended
their discussions as an invitee. The meeting focused on proposals
under discussion by the world's financial leaders on how to
contain financial turmoil and rescue countries in trouble. 
</P>
