<HEADLINE> Environmental Protection: Everyone's Care and Share </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Amid reports of deteriorating
ecological environment in a number of regions in China and under
the pressure of population and economic growth, a growing part of
the Chinese public is taking action on their own to protect the
environment.
</P>
<P>
When Green Earth Volunteers, an informal group of environmental
enthusiasts based in Beijing, organized a trip to plant trees in a
desert in Inner Mongolia last April, more than 200 people aged
from three to 75 signed up to join, doubling the organizers'
original plan of 100.
</P>
<P>
"Desertification is a grave problem in China now," said Wang,
Yongchen, one of the founders of Green Earth and an organizer of
the trip. According to the National Administration of Foresty,
every year China loses 2,600 square kilometers of farmland to
desertification. Overall, desertification affects 400 million
people in the country and causes 54 billion yuan (6.7 billion US
dollars) of economic damages a year.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot wait and see our homeland devastated by deserts,"
Wang said. "We believe that so long as we take action, the desert
can be held at bay."
</P>
<P>
Wang and several other environmentalists founded Green Earth
Volunteers in 1994 in the belief that environmental protection
should become "every citizen's care and share."
</P>
<P>
Since the launch of Green Earth Volunteers in 1994, nearly
5,000 people have participated in their diverse activities of
bird-watching, tree planting and adopting, campaigning to rescue
the Yangtze Dolphin, the most endangered dolphin in the world that
is unique and indigenous to China.
</P>
<P>
Green Earth Volunteers is only one example of people's
spontaneous environmental protection activities across China in
the past few years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981004.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
