<HEADLINE> Albanian Drug Traffickers Quicken Business in Bulgaria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Albanian drug traffickers have
stepped up their dealings in Bulgaria in the wake of the crisis in
Kosovo, an official of the National Service for Organized Crime
Control (NSOCC) said.
</P>
<P>
Drug trafficking rings are mainly controlled by Turkish, Arab
and Albanian organizations. The NSOCC Drugs Control Department
said that all Albanians, Turks and Arabs living in Bulgaria will
be extradited from the country within 24 hours when they are found
trafficking drugs.
</P>
<P>
In the early 1990s, well-armed groups became involved in the
narcotics business and in corrupting customs officials and civil
servants.
</P>
<P>
NSOCC data show that most of the drug enters Western Europe
through Iran, Turkey, the former Soviet republics in Central Asia
and Poland, while some other is trafficked through Afghanistan,
Azerbaijan, Georgia and Turkey before it reaches the Balkan route.
</P>
<P>
This year 322 kilograms of heroin has been seized in Bulgaria,
three times as much as that in Romania and Greece. Thirty-five
Bulgarians and three Macedonians have been arrested in attempts to
smuggle heroin and 49 Bulgarians caught for illegally carrying
marijuana. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981004.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Environmental Protection: Everyone's Care and Share </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In Fuzhou, capital of east China's Fujian Province, 600
volunteers from 18 environment-caring societies have been
supervising the city's environmental protection work for some 15
years.
</P>
<P>
They have signed contracts with more than 400 enterprises and
government institutions, in which leading officials pledge to
observe environmental protection laws, control discharges and
minimize noise pollution in order to nurture a desirable
environment for people in the coastal city. In 1994, they helped
eliminate more than 60 noise-pollution sources in four
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
Another environmentally-conscious non-government organization in
Beijing -- Friends of Nature -- has held lectures, organized summer
camps and published books on environmental protection since its
establishment in 1994. It also conducts a media survey on
environment reporting every year.
</P>
<P>
According to a survey of more than 500 people in Hebei Province
in 1997, nearly 68 percent of respondents were unsatisfied with the
environment surrounding them, reported the newspaper Hebei
Daily. "But only four percent of them thought of taking some
action on their own to improve their environment," said Zhao Bing,
an editor of the paper.
</P>
<P>
This means that there is a huge amount of work to do to alert
and motivate the public to be concerned about and take action on
environmental issues, Zhao said.
</P>
<P>
That is why many legislators and officials welcome environment
volunteers. Qu Geping, chairman of the Environmental and Resources
Protection Committee (ERPC) of the National People's Congress,
China's top legislature, said the emergence of
environment-conscious NGOs and volunteers "is a good thing for
China."
</P>
<P>
In fact, he said, China's environmental protection undertaking
has started and developed thanks to popular participation,
pressure and supervision. "We should encourage more participation
and supervision."
</P>
<P>
Helping prompt awareness, participation and supervision, 37
cities including Beijing and Shanghai have started announcing
local air pollution indexes (APIs) on a weekly basis in the
press. Almost all urbanites are talking about pollution and
environment. "That will hopefully be a prelude to action," said
Wang of Green Earth Volunteers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
