<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombian Political Parties Agree on Reform Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, October 3 (Xinhua) -- The Colombian
government and major political parties and movements Friday night
arrived at their first agreement aimed at realizing a deep-going
political reform in the southern American country.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, President Andres Pastrana will be given
special faculties such as "presidential pardon" to acquit rebels
to promote national peace process, the local press reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached after a seven-hour-long debate
attended by representatives of Colombia's two largest parties, the
Liberal Party and Conservative Party, and several independents
including Horacio Serpa and Noemi Sanin.
</P>
<P>
They agreed to carry out a series of reforms which will affect
the legislature and campaigning parties, and will give the
government juridical instruments for the implementation of the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
Also under planned reform is the Congress, where the number of
members would be reduced from the current 162 to 100 in the House
of Representatives, and from 100 to 60 or 80 in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
A more detailed agreement on political reform is expected to be
presented to the Congress next Tuesday. If approved in December,
it will be submitted to a referendum next year, Interior Ministry
sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
