<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trimming China's Government Establishment (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 4 (Xinhua) -- The number and size of
China's central government's ministries and commissions, formerly
40 in number, have been reduced to 29.
</P>
<P>
"The goals of the government restructuring are to establish an
administrative system that works with high efficiency, that
functions in a coordinated way and follows standard procedures;
that improves the country's civil service system and nurtures
administrative personnels that are highly competent," said State
Councillor Luo Gan at the Ninth National People's Congress.
</P>
<P>
Of the original 40 central government departments, 15 were
axed, while four new ministries and commissions were
established. Three were renamed.
</P>
<P>
Among the abolished ministries were those of the electric
power, coal and the metallurgical industries.
</P>
<P>
Under the old system, the government took charge of everything
relating to state-owned enterprises, from production to management
to marketing. Government controls more often than not led to
non-accountability and poor decision-making in the economic field.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the central government spent 1.35 billion
yuan in 1996 supporting 42,600 employees in government
institutions with iron-rice bowl lives. Nationwide, the
livelihoods of some eight million civil servants and over 28
million employees in government institutions and offices at
various levels lived off state funds. The burden became so huge
that the fundamental operations of government in various areas
such as education and research were themselves in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
In describing the situation at a press conference to outline
the government's restructuring plans, Premier Zhu Rongji told
journalists: "The government now lacks money for education, science
and technology. Where has all the money gone? It's been eaten up."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
