<DOCNO> XIE19981004.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trimming China's Government Establishment (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
All remaining 29 ministries and commissions, and other
departments under the State Council, have worked out programs to
determine their function, structure and size.
</P>
<P>
More than 200 ministerial and commission responsibilities have
been delegated to enterprises, organizations, and local
governments, while more than 100 other such functions have been
divided among State Council departments. More than 200 lower-level
departments have been cut. In all, China's government workforce
has been downsized by 47.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
Other great changes have occurred throughout the civil
service. The government structural reform has involved the
establishment and adjustment of leadership lineups in 82
ministries, commissions, institutions and offices under the State
Council, as well as state bureaus and financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
A total of 515 ranked officials have been involved. Among them,
36.1 percent have been asked to remain in their original posts,
48.2 percent have been newly-appointed and 15.7 percent have been
transferred to other posts or retired.
</P>
<P>
Some high-ranking officials were among those
affected. Seventeen ministerial-level officials are now taking
vice-ministerial-level posts, and 28 vice-ministerial-level
officials are taking vice-bureau-level posts.
</P>
<P>
In the wake of these adjustments, job assignment and provision
of proper arrangements for redundant personnel should not be
forgotten, as Premier Zhu outlined. He has targeted a three year
period for redundant personnel to find new posts after receiving
professional training. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
