<HEADLINE> Office Rental Costs Fall in Beijing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, October 4 (Xinhua) -- Increasing supply of office
space in Beijing have brought down the city's office rental costs
by as much as 50 percent since the market peak in 1995, according
to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The vacancy rate for grade-A office stock is 36 percent, and it
is projected to reach 40 percent before the market turns.
</P>
<P>
"While the city's office supply looks set to continue growing
for 1999 and 2000, it must be remembered that Beijing is a
emerging market," said Rober Walker of international property
consultant Jones Lang Wootton.
</P>
<P>
Walker, who is the managing director of the company's Beijing
Office, said the market is heading toward equilibrium from acute
shortage of quality office stock in the early and mid-1990 when
office rentals were historically high.
</P>
<P>
As construction projects are deferred and property market
schedules are put off, the supply in 1998 is likely to be only
600,000-650,000 square meters in stead of the forecast figure at
the beginning of the year, 950,000 square meters.
</P>
<P>
The steady supply serves to stabilize market conditions
allowing appropriate time for the establishment of market rentals,
Walker said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
