Zealand-Australia-Election)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ATHENS -- Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis, Bulgarian
President Petar Stoyanov and Romanian President Emil
Constantinescu Saturday met in Delphi, Greece to discuss ways of
promoting cooperation among the three countries and the situation
in the Balkan region.
</P>
<P>
During the two-day tripartite meeting, the leaders would also
discuss the planned summit meeting of Balkan countries in Turkey
and the prospects for entry into the European Union (EU) and the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) by Bulgaria and Romania,
according to the semi-official Athens News Agency (ANA).
(Greece-Romania-Meeting)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The G-24 developing countries Saturday urged the
world's industrial powers to ease monetary policy to restore
tranquility to the world financial markets.
</P>
<P>
In a communique issued in the wake of their 60th ministerial
meeting, the Intergovernmental Group of 24 On International
Monetary Affairs, which represents 128 developing nations noted,
the financial crises witnessed in the Asian region and Russia have
seriously damaged their development efforts and the severe
consequences of these crises on the world economy have been
compounded by the sharp recession in Japan. (G24-Monetary Policy)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The United Nations was investigating its
mission in Cyprus for possible abuses over access to duty-free
liquor and cigarettes, U.N. spokesman's office announced on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman's office said the possible abuse by a small
number of members of the United Nations Peace keeping Force in
Cyprus (UNFICYP) was discovered by a routine UNFICYP check and an
investigation immediately began. (UN-UNFICYP-Investigation)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton Saturday called
leaders of Britain and France on the proposal he put forward
Friday on the overhaul of the world's financial system.
</P>
<P>
Clinton telephoned British Prime Minister Tony Blair and French
President Jacques Chirac, and they favored the U.S. approach, said
White House Spokesman Joe Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
Central to the U.S. idea is to use the International Monetary
Fund (IMF) to provide more money, faster, to countries threatened
with a flight of panicked investors. (US-Finance-Clinton)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Group of Seven financial leaders met here on
Saturday to find ways to put an end to mounting global financial
turmoil.
</P>
<P>
The high-level meetings of finance ministers and central bank
governors from the G-7 -- the United States, Japan, Germany,
Britain, France, Italy and Canada -- focuses on Japan's economic
revival, regional financial crisis and discuss rescuing proposals,
including a "new mechanism" launched by U.S. President Bill
Clinton on Friday. (BC-US-G-7-Crisis)
</P>
