<HEADLINE> More Forest Fires Occur in Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, October 4 (Xinhua) -- As many as 1,542 forest fires
occurred in Vietnam in the first nine months of this year,
official Vietnam News Agency (VNA) reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The fires, a six-fold increase over that of the same period
last year, destroyed 19,214 hectares of forest, including 6,300
hectares of natural forests and 7,400 hectares of planted forests,
VNA quoted the Forestry Department under the Ministry of
Agriculture and Rural Development as saying.
</P>
<P>
Total loss was estimated at 33 billion VN dong (roughly 2.5
million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Increases in forest fires were attributed to the El Nino
phenomenon which caused prolonged droughts, consequently water
shortage in many areas for a long time and flammable forests.
</P>
<P>
The practice of slash-and-burn farming by inhabitants, mostly
ethnic minority people, in remote areas was another cause while
fire fighting facilities were degenerated.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, more than 40,000 cases of forest violation
were discovered with 455 cases being handled under the Civil Code.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese government is implementing a project to plant
five million hectares of new forests nationwide in ten years. It
aims to raise the country's forest coverage from 28 percent at
present to 43 percent in 2010. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
