<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> G-24 Developing Countries Urge G-7 Powers to Ease </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 3 (Xinhua) - The G-24 developing countries
Saturday urged the world's industrial powers to ease monetary
policy to restore tranquility to the world financial markets.
</P>
<P>
In a communique issued in the wake of their 60th ministerial
meeting, the Intergovernmental Group of 24 On International
Monetary Affairs, which represents 128 developing nations noted,
the financial crises witnessed in the Asian region and Russia have
seriously damaged their development efforts and the severe
consequences of these crises on the world economy have been
compounded by the sharp recession in Japan.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the direct contagion effects and spillovers from
market to market and from country to country, a generalized loss
of confidence has resulted in unsustainable pressure on the
exchange rate and the capital and current accounts in many parts
of the world, the communique said.
</P>
<P>
Contemporaneously, financial markets have exhibited volatility
which has resulted in higher interest rate spreads and the sharp
slowing down of private capital flows to developing countries,
leading to significant slowdown in economic activity. The
substantial fall in commodity prices is adding to the
difficulties faced by many countries and to deflationary
pressures on the global economy. Many developing countries have
suffered the loss of income, production and export opportunities,
while industrial countries have begun to feel the effects of the
crises through large decline in stock markets, pressures on their
financial institutions, and lower exports, the document noted.
</P>
<P>
The G-24 ministers called for an easing of monetary conditions
in major industrial nations and urged Japan to adopt a more
expansionary fiscal policy and to take effective action to address
the problems in its troubled banking system.
</P>
<P>
They said easing of monetary policy by major industrial nations
would help restore confidence in international financial markets,
stem outflows of capital from emerging markets and relieve heavy
debt-servicing costs.
</P>
<P>
The participants also expressed their concern that debt
workouts for heavily indebted poor countries (HIPCs) were slow and
inadequate.
</P>
<P>
Brazil, Mexico, Argentina and Venezuela, threatened by
contagion from the Asian and Russian crises, are members of the
group, which is asking for greater representation in world talks
on reshaping the world financial system.
</P>
<P>
The communique called for a more cautious freeing up capital
movements prescribed by the IMF, saying the pace should depend on
the situation of each country.
</P>
<P>
The Group said developing countries should be able to take
steps to "oversee cross-border exposure of private sector
entities, and to curb excessive speculative activity in their
foreign exchange and equity markets."
</P>
<P>
The developing countries also complained about the recent
increase in interest rates the World Bank charges them, saying the
move was not helpful at a time of financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank decided on July 31 to increase to 75 basis
points from 50 the spread it charges borrowers above funding
costs. It also decided to add a front end fee of 100 basis points.
</P>
<P>
The G-24 meeting is part of the on-going IMF-World Bank joint
annual meeting. China is not member of the G-24, but attended
their discussions as an invitee. The meeting focused on proposals
under discussion by the world's financial leaders on how to
contain financial turmoil and rescue countries in trouble.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
