<HEADLINE> G-7 Finance Leaders Meet to Head Off Global Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 3 (Xinhua) -- Group of Seven financial
leaders met here on Saturday to find ways to put an end to
mounting global financial turmoil.
</P>
<P>
The high-level meetings of finance ministers and central bank
governors from the G-7 -- the United States, Japan, Germany,
Britain, France, Italy and Canada -- focuses on Japan's economic
revival, regional financial crisis and discuss rescuing proposals,
including a "new mechanism" launched by U.S. President Bill
Clinton on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Advance to the G-7 meeting Saturday, financial leaders from
Japan and six other Asian countries -- South Korea, Indonesia,
Malaysia, Philippines, Singapore and Thailand -- held a meeting
and agreed take measures to stimulate their economies and welcomed
a 30 billion U.S. dollars aid offer from Tokyo to help the six
nations to overcome the difficulties.
</P>
<P>
The White House, which has proposed its own set of ideas to
halt the global crisis, welcomed the Japanese plan but quickly
reiterated its long-standing demands that Tokyo act swiftly and
boldly to put its own economic house in order.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin met his Japanese
counterpart Kiichi Miyazawa just before the G-7 meeting and a U.S.
Treasury official said Rubin welcomed the Japanese plan which
supports the objectives of President Clinton's recent call to
explore ways to promote growth and recovery in crisis countries in
Asia.
</P>
<P>
Rubin also said Japan must quickly reform its debt-ridden
banking system. Both ministers reiterated their concern over the
weakness of the Japanese yen currency.
</P>
<P>
The crisis that started in Asia last year has spread to Russia
and is now threatening to engulf Latin America, as frightened
investors stampede out of emerging economies across the globe -- a
phenomenon known as contagion.
</P>
<P>
The G7 is looking at possible remedies ahead of next week's
meetings of the 182-nation International Monetary Fund (IMF) and
the World Bank, which will also focus on the deepening crisis.
</P>
<P>
Saying the world financial system was facing its worst crisis
in half a century, Clinton vowed on Friday that Washington would
work with its G-7 and IMF partners to give cash-strapped nations
easier and faster access to fresh capital in times of crisis.


nnnn
05:24 05:25 g # NAB
</P>
