<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Calls Blair, Chirac on World Financial System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, October 3 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Saturday called leaders of Britain and France on the proposal he
put forward Friday on the overhaul of the world's financial
system.
</P>
<P>
Clinton telephoned British Prime Minister Tony Blair and French
President Jacques Chirac, and they favored the U.S. approach, said
White House Spokesman Joe Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
Central to the U.S. idea is to use the International Monetary
Fund (IMF) to provide more money, faster, to countries threatened
with a flight of panicked investors.
</P>
<P>
Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin and Federal Reserve Chairman
Alan Greenspan, who helped develop the proposals, sought the
endorsements of finance ministers and central bank governors from
the world's seven richest countries.
</P>
<P>
Top financial officials of the G-7 nations gathered at the
Blair House located near the White House.
</P>
<P>
Clinton announced on Friday his nation would work with its
partners to forge a "new mechanism" to provide fresh money for
cash-strapped nations around the world.
</P>
<P>
The aim of such a new facility, anchored in the IMF, would be
"to provide contingent finance to help countries ward off global
financial contagion."
</P>
<P>
Clinton said Rubin and Greenspan would explore the possibility
with their counterparts from the major industrial Group of Seven
(G-7) nations.
</P>
<P>
He also said he was asking international financial leaders "to
lend quickly so as to help other countries reform their financial
sectors while also helping the most vulnerable citizens."
</P>
<P>
He called on multilateral lenders "to use loan guarantees and
other innovative means to leverage private-sector lending to
emerging markets, and to expand their own lending as much as
possible within their guidelines to countries effected by the
crisis who desperately need an infusion of new cash."
</P>
<P>
The president said Washington had held "constructive" early
discussions with its G-7 partners about the proposal and the G-7
financial leaders will discuss over the weekend about exactly how
that would work. 
</P>
</TEXT>
